  <i> a lot on Napoleon, I think.</i>  

382
00:23:33,445 --> 00:23:35,479
     - That's an interesting    
     thing for--                
     -<i> Yeah.</i>                    

383
00:23:35,581 --> 00:23:38,047
      <i> No, she was really,</i>      
      <i> truly extraordinary.</i>     

384
00:23:38,149 --> 00:23:40,984
            <i> I mean,</i>            
     <i> she was like a force.</i>     

385
00:23:41,086 --> 00:23:45,288
    If she decided she wanted   
     something, she got it.     

386
00:23:45,391 --> 00:23:47,891
        <i> She was plotting</i>       
         <i> all the time.</i>         

387
00:23:47,993 --> 00:23:50,360
    - She liked to...           
    - She had schemes going.    

388
00:23:50,462 --> 00:23:52,028
             ...stir up things, 
             you know?          

389
00:23:52,130 --> 00:23:54,831
 And then my mother fell in love
     with Prince Hohenlohe.     

390
00:23:54,933 --> 00:23:58,034
     <i> And that's what really</i>    
          <i> set her off.</i>         

391
00:23:58,136 --> 00:23:59,969
             Cooper:            
    <i> He was a German prince.</i>    

392
00:24:00,071 --> 00:24:02,038
           Vanderbilt:          
      <i> The prince was fine,</i>     
    <i> but that he was German--</i>   

393
00:24:02,140 --> 00:24:04,741
   <i> she was really hysterical</i>   
         <i> about Germans.</i>        

394
00:24:07,913 --> 00:24:11,147
   The idea that her daughter   
   was gonna marry this German  

395
00:24:11,249 --> 00:24:14,250
     and take my mother off     
       to live in Bavaria       

396
00:24:14,352 --> 00:24:17,687
         at some castle         
      made her apoplectic.      

397
00:24:17,790 --> 00:24:21,925
    And my mom's grandmother    
          began to plot         

398
00:24:22,027 --> 00:24:25,028
       <i> a way to stop this</i>      
        <i> from happening.</i>        

399
00:24:25,130 --> 00:24:28,197
          She should be         
   a Vanderbilt and should be   
      in the United States.     

400
00:24:28,300 --> 00:24:30,033
   And that's her birthright.   

401
00:24:36,608 --> 00:24:38,742
           Vanderbilt:          
      <i> I used to as a child</i>     
           <i> lie in bed</i>          

402
00:24:38,844 --> 00:24:41,010
     <i> in the house in Paris</i>     
      <i> in the dark at night</i>     

403
00:24:41,112 --> 00:24:44,047
  <i> and I was afraid to go sleep</i> 
      <i> without the light on</i>     

404
00:24:44,149 --> 00:24:47,183
        <i> in the bathroom</i>        
    <i> without my nurse there.</i>    

405
00:24:47,285 --> 00:24:49,619
        So she would stay       
   in the bathroom every night  

406
00:24:49,721 --> 00:24:52,889
     <i> until I went to sleep.</i>    

407
00:24:52,991 --> 00:24:54,524
      <i> Then my grandmother</i>      
         <i> would come in</i>         

408
00:24:54,626 --> 00:24:56,326
        <i> and that's when</i>        
       <i> I would hear them</i>       

409
00:24:56,428 --> 00:24:58,595
     <i> whispering, you know?</i>     

410
00:24:58,697 --> 00:25:02,031
      ( voices whispering )     

411
00:25:02,133 --> 00:25:05,301
    It was like something was   
   being plotted and planned.   

412
00:25:05,403 --> 00:25:08,672
             Cooper:            
     <i> My mom's grandmother,</i>     
      <i> Grandmother Morgan,</i>      

413
00:25:08,774 --> 00:25:12,542
       <i> hatched this plan</i>       
      <i> with my mom's nanny.</i>     

414
00:25:12,644 --> 00:25:15,378
     <i> Why do you think Dodo</i>     
   <i> went along with the plan?</i>   

415
00:25:15,481 --> 00:25:18,247
           Vanderbilt:          
      <i> Because she totally</i>      
        <i> agreed with it.</i>        

416
00:25:18,350 --> 00:25:21,885
   She always thought I should  
    be brought up in America    

417
00:25:21,987 --> 00:25:24,087
          'cause I was          
        an American girl.       

418
00:25:24,189 --> 00:25:26,490
             Cooper:            
        <i> It's crazy to me</i>       
   <i> that that's how it began.</i>   

419
00:25:26,592 --> 00:25:28,892
    <i> That that's how sort of</i>    
      <i> the seed was planted</i>     

420
00:25:28,994 --> 00:25:31,962
    and grew into this thing    
    which completely changed    

421
00:25:32,063 --> 00:25:33,697
           the course           
    of my mom's life forever.   

422
00:25:33,799 --> 00:25:38,234
         I mean, I would        
     have been happy to stay    
       in Paris with Dodo.      

423
00:25:38,336 --> 00:25:40,470
      That would have been      
     the right thing for me.    

424
00:25:40,572 --> 00:25:45,341
     I mean, it would have--    
      I mean, I was happy.      

425
00:25:45,443 --> 00:25:48,745
             Cooper:            
  <i> But my mom was brought back</i>  
      <i> to the United States</i>     

426
00:25:48,847 --> 00:25:53,016
  <i> by her nurse and grandmother</i> 
      <i> to her aunt's house.</i>     

427
00:25:53,118 --> 00:25:55,485
      "We were on our way,      
         all three of us        

428
00:25:55,587 --> 00:25:57,654
        on an ocean liner       
      called the Majestic.      

429
00:25:57,756 --> 00:25:59,956
          <i> I had a new</i>          
        <i> rabbit fur coat</i>        

430
00:26:00,058 --> 00:26:02,926
    <i> and Nanny Morgan gave me</i>   
       <i> an American flag.</i>       

431
00:26:03,028 --> 00:26:05,896
       <i> Soon I would meet</i>       
       <i> my Aunt Gertrude.</i>       

432
00:26:05,998 --> 00:26:08,665
       <i> She was the sister</i>      
         <i> of my father,</i>         

433
00:26:08,767 --> 00:26:10,767
         <i> the one I made</i>        
       <i> the paper doll of.</i>      

434
00:26:10,869 --> 00:26:13,537
         <i> And she lived</i>         
        <i> in New York City</i>       
          <i> in a castle.</i>         

435
00:26:13,639 --> 00:26:17,106
    I kept going over things    
   I wanted to ask her about.   

436
00:26:17,208 --> 00:26:19,943
   'What was my father like?'   
       Things like that."       

437
00:26:20,045 --> 00:26:22,679
           Vanderbilt:          
          <i> I was living</i>         
       <i> at Aunt Gertrude's</i>      

438
00:26:22,781 --> 00:26:24,848
         <i> and my mother</i>         
      <i> was still in Europe.</i>     

439
00:26:24,950 --> 00:26:26,583
     <i> And then she came back</i>    

440
00:26:26,685 --> 00:26:29,886
     because she was living     
     off of my inheritance,     
          so to speak.          

441
00:26:29,988 --> 00:26:32,856
       <i> My father had not</i>       
       <i> left her any money</i>      

442
00:26:32,958 --> 00:26:35,224
        <i> because he knew</i>        
   <i> she would be taken care of</i>  

443
00:26:35,326 --> 00:26:37,493
         because of me,         
            you know?           

444
00:26:42,634 --> 00:26:47,437
          <i> So my mother</i>         
   <i> really was forced to rent</i>   
    <i> a house on 72nd Street.</i>    

445
00:26:47,505 --> 00:26:51,041
         <i> I was in there</i>        
         <i> for a weekend</i>         

446
00:26:51,142 --> 00:26:55,045
    <i> and I heard her talking</i>    
      <i> to her older sister</i>      

447
00:26:55,146 --> 00:26:58,481
          <i> and saying,</i>          
     <i> "Well, the first thing</i>    
         <i> we have to do</i>         

448
00:26:58,584 --> 00:27:01,250
           is get rid           
         of the nurse."         

449
00:27:01,352 --> 00:27:05,388
       And I overheard her      
      saying that and I got     
     absolutely hysterical.     

450
00:27:06,792 --> 00:27:08,959
   <i> I mean, she was my mother,</i>  
           <i> my father.</i>          

451
00:27:09,061 --> 00:27:10,226
      <i> She was everything.</i>      

452
00:27:10,328 --> 00:27:13,229
      She was my lifeline.      
       She was all I had.       

453
00:27:13,331 --> 00:27:14,764
     <i> ( voices whispering )</i>     

454
00:27:14,866 --> 00:27:17,634
    <i> Well, I went up to Dodo</i>    
       <i> screaming, crying,</i>      

455
00:27:17,736 --> 00:27:19,502
          <i> and told her</i>         
     <i> what I had overheard.</i>     

456
00:27:19,605 --> 00:27:23,439
           <i> She said,</i>           
    <i> "Just be calm, be quiet.</i>   

457
00:27:23,541 --> 00:27:26,876
       <i> We're going to go</i>       
     <i> as if we're going out</i>     
          <i> to the park</i>          

458
00:27:26,979 --> 00:27:31,280
    <i> and we'll get in the car</i>   
    <i> and we're gonna go down</i>    
      <i> to Aunt Gertrude's."</i>     

459
00:27:31,382 --> 00:27:33,349
      <i> And then the minute</i>      
       <i> I got in the car,</i>       

460
00:27:33,451 --> 00:27:36,019
       <i> I just absolutely</i>       
           <i> collapsed.</i>          

461
00:27:37,689 --> 00:27:40,624
             Cooper:            
      <i> And my mom was taken</i>     
          <i> by her nurse</i>         

462
00:27:40,726 --> 00:27:43,392
     <i> to her aunt's studio.</i>     

463
00:27:57,075 --> 00:28:00,777
    The last time I was here,   
           I was nine.          

464
00:28:05,550 --> 00:28:09,418
        <i> There are rooms</i>        
       <i> that wait for us.</i>       

465
00:28:09,521 --> 00:28:13,356
       <i> And someday we may</i>      
        <i> be in that room</i>        

466
00:28:13,458 --> 00:28:18,762
    <i> and something may happen</i>   
     <i> to us that may change</i>     
       <i> our life forever.</i>       

467
00:28:24,636 --> 00:28:27,103
           <i> When Dodo</i>           
       <i> took me down here,</i>      

468
00:28:27,205 --> 00:28:29,806
          Aunt Gertrude         
        was in this room.       

469
00:28:29,908 --> 00:28:34,377
         And then there         
        was a sofa there        
     and another sofa here.     

470
00:28:34,479 --> 00:28:37,047
          <i> I was really</i>         
        <i> just hysterical,</i>       

471
00:28:37,149 --> 00:28:40,917
      <i> so they got doctors</i>      
     <i> to come and they tried</i>    
          <i> to calm me.</i>          

472
00:28:41,019 --> 00:28:43,019
     And I never went back.     

473
00:28:44,723 --> 00:28:47,857
  When they questioned whether  
     her mother was capable     

474
00:28:47,959 --> 00:28:50,426
           of raising           
       the child properly,      

475
00:28:50,528 --> 00:28:53,663
        Gertrude decided        
      that she wanted to go     
          for custody.          

476
00:28:58,436 --> 00:29:00,336
       <i> Although Gertrude,</i>      

477
00:29:00,438 --> 00:29:03,807
     <i> I think her intentions</i>    
  <i> were the best they could be,</i> 

478
00:29:03,909 --> 00:29:08,611
    I'm not sure that warmth    
  was her main personal trait.  

479
00:29:11,683 --> 00:29:12,949
             Cooper:            
  <i> Do you think she loved you?</i>  

480
00:29:13,051 --> 00:29:14,918
        I think she did.        
              I do.             

481
00:29:15,020 --> 00:29:17,520
      I think she couldn't      
      break out of herself.     

482
00:29:19,725 --> 00:29:22,358
    <i> She'd come up at night,</i>    
     <i> I'd be in bed already</i>     

483
00:29:22,460 --> 00:29:25,494
   <i> and she would come and sit</i>  
  <i> on my bed to say good night.</i> 

484
00:29:25,597 --> 00:29:28,331
         Once she said,         
      "I love you so much."     

485
00:29:28,433 --> 00:29:30,033
    And I was so embarrassed    

486
00:29:30,135 --> 00:29:34,170
   because she had always been  
   so remote and kind of cold   

487
00:29:34,272 --> 00:29:38,241
      and it was so kind of     
      unexpected, you know?     

488
00:29:39,677 --> 00:29:41,377
        <i> Did you tell her</i>       
      <i> that you loved her?</i>      

489
00:29:41,479 --> 00:29:42,879
              Yes.              

490
00:29:48,153 --> 00:29:51,020
   <i> I think she did it because</i>  
    <i> she really truly thought</i>   

491
00:29:51,123 --> 00:29:54,157
     <i> it was the best thing</i>     
       <i> for her niece, me.</i>      

492
00:29:54,259 --> 00:29:57,193
   And she had been very close  
    to my father, apparently.   

493
00:29:57,295 --> 00:29:59,763
   <i> But we never spoke of it.</i>   

494
00:30:01,733 --> 00:30:03,499
             Alfred:            
    <i> So you had both Gertrude</i>   
      <i> and the grandmother</i>      

495
00:30:03,601 --> 00:30:06,702
       <i> trying to separate</i>      
    <i> Gloria from her mother.</i>    

496
00:30:06,805 --> 00:30:09,405
      Imagine being a child     
     and having that happen.    

497
00:30:11,042 --> 00:30:13,810
           Vanderbilt:          
        <i> I was terrified</i>        
          <i> of my mother</i>         

498
00:30:13,912 --> 00:30:16,946
   <i> because I thought she was</i>   
    <i> going to take Dodo away.</i>   

499
00:30:22,220 --> 00:30:25,655
             Alfred:            
      <i> It was a tremendous</i>      
         <i> press bonanza.</i>        

500
00:30:25,757 --> 00:30:27,924
   <i> Tremendous amount of media</i>  
          <i> in New York</i>          

501
00:30:28,026 --> 00:30:30,894
      <i> and it was the case</i>      
 <i> of the poor little rich girl.</i> 

502
00:30:30,996 --> 00:30:34,798
 <i> Now, this was still at a time</i> 
    <i> where a million dollars</i>    

503
00:30:34,900 --> 00:30:38,101
    was beyond the imaginings   
         of most people.        

504
00:30:38,203 --> 00:30:40,603
         <i> Most families</i>         
         <i> in the country</i>        

505
00:30:40,705 --> 00:30:43,273
     <i> were trying to get by</i>     
        <i> on $10 a month.</i>        

506
00:30:43,374 --> 00:30:45,809
           Vanderbilt:          
       <i> It was the height</i>       
       <i> of the Depression.</i>      

507
00:30:45,911 --> 00:30:49,578
  <i> That's, I think, why people</i>  
  <i> were so fascinated with it.</i>  

508
00:30:49,681 --> 00:30:53,449
   <i> You know, saw this family</i>   
 <i> that apparently had everything</i>

509
00:30:53,551 --> 00:30:57,420
           and-- and--          

510
00:30:57,522 --> 00:30:58,888
            you know.           

511
00:31:01,092 --> 00:31:03,993
 <i> I knew that something terrible</i>
    <i> was going to come about</i>    

512
00:31:04,095 --> 00:31:08,331
      <i> because they closed</i>      
   <i> any audience being there.</i>   

513
00:31:12,403 --> 00:31:14,770
        <i> My mother's maid</i>       
         <i> had testified</i>         

514
00:31:14,873 --> 00:31:17,807
     and said that my mother    
          was a lesbian         

515
00:31:17,909 --> 00:31:21,044
    and that she had seen her   

516
00:31:21,146 --> 00:31:24,180
        making love with        
       Lady Milford Haven,      

517
00:31:24,282 --> 00:31:27,917
      who she was visiting.     

518
00:31:28,019 --> 00:31:31,955
   <i> In those days, of course,</i>   
      <i> that was considered</i>      

519
00:31:32,057 --> 00:31:34,623
       <i> strange, you know?</i>      

520
00:31:47,839 --> 00:31:50,473
             Alfred:            
        <i> To have a child</i>        
      <i> sort of on the loose</i>     

521
00:31:50,575 --> 00:31:53,076
     <i> with someone who's not</i>    
       <i> very responsible,</i>       

522
00:31:53,178 --> 00:31:57,180
     <i> it's not unreasonable</i>     
    <i> to have wanted to help.</i>    

523
00:32:08,760 --> 00:32:10,894
      I think that's enough     
           for today.           

524
00:32:17,502 --> 00:32:20,136
       The horrible irony       
   is one of the first things   
          the judge did         

525
00:32:20,238 --> 00:32:22,939
    after taking my mom away    
       from her own mother      

526
00:32:23,041 --> 00:32:25,508
        <i> was getting rid</i>        
     <i> of the nurse as well.</i>     

527
00:32:25,610 --> 00:32:27,743
           Vanderbilt:          
    <i> My mother's lawyer said</i>    

528
00:32:27,845 --> 00:32:31,814
  <i> that she was influencing me</i>  
       <i> against my mother.</i>      

529
00:32:31,917 --> 00:32:34,984
         <i> And that's why</i>        
      <i> they took her away.</i>      

530
00:32:37,555 --> 00:32:41,724
         So all my hopes        

531
00:32:41,826 --> 00:32:45,728
         were, you know,        
     all for naught, really.    

532
00:32:57,775 --> 00:33:00,509
      <i> I have inside of me</i>      

533
00:33:00,611 --> 00:33:03,913
     <i> an image of a shining,</i>    

534
00:33:04,015 --> 00:33:07,516
      rock-hard diamond...      

535
00:33:09,821 --> 00:33:12,455
         that no matter         
       what happens to me,      

536
00:33:12,557 --> 00:33:15,724
          nothing can--         
             can...             

537
00:33:19,130 --> 00:33:21,097
             get at             

538
00:33:21,199 --> 00:33:26,135
           or crack...          

539
00:33:38,483 --> 00:33:41,217
   And I've always known that   
          about myself.         

540
00:34:23,461 --> 00:34:25,461
           Announcer:           
       <i> Gloria Vanderbilt,</i>      
       <i> once storm center</i>       

541
00:34:25,563 --> 00:34:29,198
 <i> of a sensational court battle,</i>
     <i> is going on 13 now...</i>     

542
00:34:29,300 --> 00:34:31,867
           Vanderbilt:          
 <i> I never felt that I belonged.</i> 

543
00:34:33,938 --> 00:34:36,805
        You know, I felt        
        I was an imposter       

544
00:34:36,908 --> 00:34:39,308
   <i> and kind of a changeling.</i>   

545
00:34:42,813 --> 00:34:44,947
           Gloria was           
      that outsider person.     

546
00:34:45,050 --> 00:34:49,519
       <i> She was not quite</i>       
   <i> a Whitney and she was not</i>   
      <i> quite a Vanderbilt.</i>      

547
00:34:49,620 --> 00:34:53,022
        She really seems        
     to have raised herself.    

548
00:34:53,124 --> 00:34:56,959
     <i> But Gloria did grow up</i>    
    <i> in Gertrude's household.</i>   

549
00:34:57,062 --> 00:34:58,327
     Gertrude was an artist.    

550
00:34:58,430 --> 00:35:01,264
    She was a serious artist,   
          a sculptress.         

551
00:35:01,366 --> 00:35:03,266
     And clearly Gloria got     
          some of that.         

552
00:35:03,368 --> 00:35:06,702
           Vanderbilt:          
      <i> These are very early</i>     
       <i> paintings of mine.</i>      

553
00:35:06,804 --> 00:35:10,339
       - A long time ago?       
       - A long time ago.       
       Way, way back.           

554
00:35:10,442 --> 00:35:13,543
    - Okay.                     
    - I'd love to have these    
    in the studio.              

555
00:35:13,644 --> 00:35:16,279
        <i> That's amazing.</i>        

556
00:35:16,381 --> 00:35:18,347
       - So you want            
       to take all these?       
       - Yes.                   

557
00:35:18,450 --> 00:35:20,550
     Okay. I mean,              
     there's piles of them.     

558
00:35:20,651 --> 00:35:23,419
    - Do you want them all?     
    - I'd like them all, yes.   

559
00:35:23,521 --> 00:35:27,356
     I think we're going to need
     a truck to take them all.  

560
00:35:27,459 --> 00:35:29,925
        I mean, these are like  
        when I was in my teens. 

561
00:35:30,027 --> 00:35:32,395
       - Really?                
       - Yeah. At Wheeler.      

562
00:35:38,403 --> 00:35:40,336
             Cooper:            
        <i> What was it like</i>       
          <i> at Wheeler?</i>          

563
00:35:40,438 --> 00:35:42,771
           Vanderbilt:          
     <i> Oh, I really loved it.</i>    

564
00:35:42,873 --> 00:35:45,575
   <i> Really the most wonderful</i>   
        <i> art department.</i>        

565
00:35:45,676 --> 00:35:47,477
        <i> They'd let me go</i>       
       <i> and work off-hours</i>      

566
00:35:47,579 --> 00:35:50,879
        <i> and a wonderful</i>        
          <i> art teacher.</i>         

567
00:35:50,982 --> 00:35:54,383
           <i> I was just</i>          
    <i> very, very happy there.</i>    

568
00:35:54,486 --> 00:35:56,352
          <i> And this was</i>         
      <i> when I first started</i>     

569
00:35:56,454 --> 00:36:00,856
    <i> really, you know, having</i>   
     <i> more sense of myself.</i>     

570
00:36:03,228 --> 00:36:06,629
    - So these are letters      
    from your Aunt Gertrude?    
    - Yes.                      

571
00:36:08,966 --> 00:36:12,135
 The interesting ones           
 are the ones--                 

572
00:36:12,237 --> 00:36:15,004
  interesting to me--           

573
00:36:15,106 --> 00:36:18,274
 when I was in California       

574
00:36:18,376 --> 00:36:21,577
 and had gone out               
 to stay with my mother         

575
00:36:21,679 --> 00:36:23,746
 for two weeks                  

576
00:36:23,848 --> 00:36:27,416
        <i> with a chaperone</i>       
       <i> called Constance.</i>       

577
00:36:32,857 --> 00:36:36,825
 My twin sister                 
 Mrs. Vanderbilt and I          

578
00:36:36,927 --> 00:36:38,694
 have just finished--           

579
00:36:38,796 --> 00:36:40,463
              Man:              
              <i> Cut.</i>             

580
00:36:40,565 --> 00:36:45,100
We are                          
concluding our trip now.        
We're in Hollywood.             

581
00:36:45,203 --> 00:36:49,004
And I want                      
to thank everybody              
for being so very nice.         

582
00:37:04,689 --> 00:37:07,390
           Vanderbilt:          
     <i> I was so movie-struck</i>     

583
00:37:07,492 --> 00:37:10,259
           <i> growing up</i>          
   <i> from the time I was nine.</i>   

584
00:37:10,361 --> 00:37:14,163
 And suddenly Errol Flynn       
 was dating me.                 

585
00:37:14,265 --> 00:37:15,731
           <i> ( Cooper laughs )</i>   
           <i> Really?</i>             

586
00:37:15,833 --> 00:37:18,767
        <i> And Ray Milland,</i>       
   <i> who was married, you know?</i>  

587
00:37:18,869 --> 00:37:22,071
   - Cooper:<i> Wait, so you were</i>  
   <i> dating Errol Flynn?</i>         
   -<i> Yes.</i>                       

588
00:37:22,173 --> 00:37:24,940
     - And how old were you?    
     - 17.                      

589
00:37:25,042 --> 00:37:27,876
           Vanderbilt:          
      <i> And I was just gaga.</i>     

590
00:37:27,978 --> 00:37:30,479
    <i> 'Cause I thought, wow...</i>   

591
00:37:30,582 --> 00:37:33,482
- And you're                    
still in high school.           
- I had another year at Wheeler.

592
00:37:33,585 --> 00:37:35,451
    I hadn't finished           
    high school.                

593
00:37:35,553 --> 00:37:37,086
             Cooper:            
          <i> And your mom</i>         
       <i> was fine with it?</i>       

594
00:37:37,188 --> 00:37:38,954
 <i> She let me</i>                    
 <i> literally do any--</i>            

595
00:37:39,056 --> 00:37:41,023
  it was like living            
  in a hotel.                   

596
00:37:41,125 --> 00:37:43,959
      - Mm-hmm.                 
      - I could do anything     
      I wanted to do.           

597
00:37:44,061 --> 00:37:48,297
     And, I mean, looking       
     back at it now,            

598
00:37:48,399 --> 00:37:50,299
      it was very terrible.     

599
00:37:50,401 --> 00:37:53,001
     You know?                  
     I mean, I would not        
     want my daughter           

600
00:37:53,104 --> 00:37:55,238
     to behave the way          
     I did, you know?           

601
00:37:56,841 --> 00:38:01,210
    But there was               
    kind of nobody around       

602
00:38:01,312 --> 00:38:04,046
      to counsel me.            

603
00:38:04,148 --> 00:38:05,581
            So Aunt Gertrude--  

604
00:38:05,683 --> 00:38:08,551
    So anyway, I wrote          
    to Aunt Gertrude to ask--   

605
00:38:08,653 --> 00:38:12,722
  to say, you know,             
  that I was going to stay on.  

606
00:38:12,823 --> 00:38:17,159
     I'm trying to find         
     the letter where she--     

607
00:38:17,262 --> 00:38:19,328
     where she says about--     

608
00:38:21,366 --> 00:38:23,966
      Oh, there's one           
      where she says,           

609
00:38:24,068 --> 00:38:26,034
       "You're being            
      talked about."            

610
00:38:26,137 --> 00:38:27,670
          - Oh, really?         
          - Oh, yes.            

611
00:38:38,583 --> 00:38:42,017
          <i> "Your letter</i>         
       <i> from Santa Barbara</i>      
     <i> came a few days ago."</i>     

612
00:38:42,119 --> 00:38:45,087
          "You know, darling."  

613
00:38:45,189 --> 00:38:47,323
          It says,              
          "You know, darling,   

614
00:38:47,425 --> 00:38:50,025
    <i> I have only your welfare</i>   
    <i> and happiness at heart.</i>    

615
00:38:50,127 --> 00:38:53,763
 <i> And when you're ready to talk</i> 
  <i> over your problems with me,</i>  

616
00:38:53,864 --> 00:38:55,765
         <i> I will be only</i>        
       <i> too happy to help</i>       

617
00:38:55,866 --> 00:38:57,566
           <i> in any way</i>          
        <i> I possibly can."</i>       

618
00:38:57,669 --> 00:39:00,670
  And you see, she had never    
  really been that way before,  

619
00:39:00,772 --> 00:39:02,971
   so it was kind of            
   too late, you know?          

620
00:39:03,073 --> 00:39:05,408
      So she never actually said
      this kind of stuff to you?

621
00:39:05,510 --> 00:39:08,210
    No, no.                     
    This was the first time.    

622
00:39:08,313 --> 00:39:09,745
        I mean...               

623
00:39:14,819 --> 00:39:18,086
      My plan was to finish     
           at Wheeler           

624
00:39:18,189 --> 00:39:20,356
           and instead          
      of going to college,      

625
00:39:20,458 --> 00:39:22,591
   to go to the Arts Students   
       League in New York.      

626
00:39:22,694 --> 00:39:24,293
           That's what          
         I wanted to do.        

627
00:39:24,395 --> 00:39:27,630
   And live at Aunt Gertrude's  
       in Washington Mews.      

628
00:39:27,732 --> 00:39:29,231
         And that's what        
        I expected to do        

629
00:39:29,334 --> 00:39:33,101
         when I went out        
    to California, you know?    

630
00:39:33,204 --> 00:39:35,571
         But, of course,        
  it didn't turn out that way.  

631
00:39:37,775 --> 00:39:40,843
    Announcer:<i> Wedding bells</i>    
   <i> at Santa Barbara's ancient</i>  
        <i> Spanish mission</i>        

632
00:39:40,945 --> 00:39:44,213
      <i> as five bridesmaids</i>      
   <i> precede Gloria Vanderbilt,</i>  

633
00:39:44,315 --> 00:39:47,450
      <i> 17-year-old daughter</i>     
  <i> of Mrs. Reginald Vanderbilt.</i> 

634
00:39:49,721 --> 00:39:51,253
             Cooper:            
        <i> Do you remember</i>        
       <i> your wedding day?</i>       

635
00:39:51,356 --> 00:39:52,822
           Oh, please.          

636
00:39:52,923 --> 00:39:55,090
<i>( laughs )</i>                      
<i>What?</i>                           

637
00:39:55,192 --> 00:39:58,861
         Best forgotten.        
    But I remember everything   
            about it.           

638
00:40:00,898 --> 00:40:03,131
       <i> As I was standing</i>       
           <i> there, I--</i>          

639
00:40:03,234 --> 00:40:05,401
       you know that movie      
       Mike Nichols made?       

640
00:40:05,503 --> 00:40:07,069
    - Was it "The Graduate"?    
    -<i> Yes.</i>                      

641
00:40:07,171 --> 00:40:10,005
 That was-- while I was up there
  I was, "What am I doing here? 

642
00:40:10,107 --> 00:40:12,441
     What am I thinking of?"    

643
00:40:12,543 --> 00:40:13,809
      And I wanted to run.      

644
00:40:13,911 --> 00:40:15,978
         But, you know,         
  where was I going to run to?  

645
00:40:16,080 --> 00:40:19,815
      Back to Aunt Gertrude     
  and the chaperone, you know?  

646
00:40:19,917 --> 00:40:23,218
    I just wanted to get out.   

647
00:40:23,320 --> 00:40:26,355
     <i> Now I can laugh at it,</i>    
           <i> you know?</i>           

648
00:40:26,457 --> 00:40:29,925
    <i> It's like something that</i>   
   <i> happened to somebody else,</i>  
           <i> you know?</i>           

649
00:40:30,027 --> 00:40:31,994
    'Cause I was a different    
          person then.          

650
00:40:32,096 --> 00:40:33,228
       ( crowd cheering )       

651
00:40:33,330 --> 00:40:34,997
           Announcer:           
    <i> He is Pasquale DiCicco,</i>    

652
00:40:35,099 --> 00:40:37,666
    <i> Hollywood actors' agent,</i>   
           <i> and is 32.</i>          

653
00:40:37,769 --> 00:40:39,535
   <i> The young bride will live</i>   
      <i> near Beverly Hills.</i>      

654
00:40:39,637 --> 00:40:41,570
             Cooper:            
        <i> He was described</i>       
     <i> as a Hollywood agent.</i>     

655
00:40:41,672 --> 00:40:44,673
      -<i> Was he an agent?</i>        
      - Well, maybe at one      
      point he was.             

656
00:40:44,776 --> 00:40:47,242
       He had been married      
         to Thelma Todd,        

657
00:40:47,344 --> 00:40:48,977
          who was quite         
      a well-known actress.     

658
00:40:49,079 --> 00:40:53,048
       And she died under       
    mysterious circumstances.   

659
00:40:53,150 --> 00:40:56,452
    There were sort of rumors   
    around that maybe he had    
      killed her, you know?     

660
00:40:56,554 --> 00:40:58,987
          ( laughing )          
         Wait a minute.         

661
00:40:59,089 --> 00:41:02,691
   So you got married to a guy  
  who there were rumors that he 
   had killed his former wife?  

662
00:41:02,794 --> 00:41:04,092
                    <i> Yes, yes.</i>  

663
00:41:04,194 --> 00:41:06,261
        Did that not seem       
       to give you pause?       

664
00:41:06,363 --> 00:41:09,665
           <i> Well, I thought</i>     
           <i> all he needs is me,</i> 
           <i> you know, to...</i>     

665
00:41:09,767 --> 00:41:12,435
            Oh, God.            

666
00:41:12,537 --> 00:41:14,737
           Sweetheart,          
         I was only 17.         

667
00:41:14,839 --> 00:41:16,405
<i>Okay.</i>                           
<i>I know.</i>                         

668
00:41:18,142 --> 00:41:20,910
      President Roosevelt:      
  <i> The United States of America</i> 

669
00:41:21,011 --> 00:41:23,746
          <i> was suddenly</i>         
   <i> and deliberately attacked</i>   

670
00:41:23,848 --> 00:41:26,949
    <i> by the Empire of Japan.</i>    

671
00:41:27,051 --> 00:41:29,117
   <i> The facts of yesterday...</i>   

672
00:41:29,219 --> 00:41:31,286
           Vanderbilt:          
        <i> We were married</i>        
          <i> December 28,</i>         

673
00:41:31,388 --> 00:41:32,922
    <i> so it had just happened.</i>   

674
00:41:33,023 --> 00:41:35,491
    <i> And he actually enrolled</i>   
         <i> in the cavalry</i>        

675
00:41:35,593 --> 00:41:38,260
           <i> very soon</i>           
       <i> after December 27.</i>      

676
00:41:38,362 --> 00:41:40,095
             Cooper:            
  <i> So you lived on an army base</i> 
         <i> for two years?</i>        

677
00:41:40,197 --> 00:41:41,864
           Vanderbilt:          
              <i> Yes.</i>             

678
00:41:44,301 --> 00:41:48,003
     Finally, just as he was    
    going to be shipped off,    
       he got septicemia.       

679
00:41:48,105 --> 00:41:50,906
       -<i> Oh, okay.</i>              
       - So he never went.      

680
00:41:51,008 --> 00:41:52,975
           Vanderbilt:          
   <i> I went to a lot of movies.</i>  

681
00:41:53,077 --> 00:41:55,578
Cooper:                         
<i>As a kid, you loved</i>             
<i>to go to the movies.</i>            

682
00:41:55,680 --> 00:41:58,280
            ( gasps )           
        Obsessed with it.       

683
00:41:58,382 --> 00:42:01,717
    I thought that's the way    
  it's gonna be when I grow up. 

684
00:42:01,819 --> 00:42:03,586
       <i> ( music playing )</i>       

685
00:42:11,195 --> 00:42:15,397
           <i>  Someday</i>           
       <i> he'll come along </i>      

686
00:42:15,500 --> 00:42:18,266
       <i>  The man I love </i>      

687
00:42:18,369 --> 00:42:23,038
         <i>  And he'll be</i>        
        <i> big and strong </i>       

688
00:42:23,140 --> 00:42:26,709
       <i>  The man I love </i>      

689
00:42:26,811 --> 00:42:30,679
      <i>  And when he comes</i>      
            <i> my way </i>           

690
00:42:30,781 --> 00:42:33,348
      <i>  I'll do my best </i>      

691
00:42:33,450 --> 00:42:39,354
    <i>  To make him stay... </i>    

692
00:42:39,456 --> 00:42:42,525
             Cooper:            
 <i> When did you realize it wasn't</i>
<i>going to work with Pat DiCicco?</i> 

693
00:42:42,627 --> 00:42:44,593
           Vanderbilt:          
   <i> Oh, well, pretty early on.</i>  

694
00:42:44,695 --> 00:42:48,163
 I mean, he gave me a black eye 
      when I was in Kansas      

695
00:42:48,265 --> 00:42:50,298
    and I went to the doctor.   

696
00:42:50,401 --> 00:42:54,136
      And I was so ashamed      
   and embarrassed, you know?   

697
00:42:54,238 --> 00:42:56,839
      And the doctor said,      
     "How did this happen?"     

698
00:42:56,941 --> 00:43:00,375
  And I said, "Well, you know,  
   I just fell on something."   

699
00:43:00,477 --> 00:43:03,679
      I was too ashamed to,     
            you know.           

700
00:43:03,781 --> 00:43:06,949
        But then I really       
       got scared of him.       
          I really did.         

701
00:43:10,087 --> 00:43:12,521
    <i> And, of course, my aunt</i>    
        <i> was very upset,</i>        

702
00:43:12,623 --> 00:43:14,957
      <i> which she certainly</i>      
       <i> should have been.</i>       

703
00:43:15,059 --> 00:43:19,828
        <i> I mean, anybody</i>        
      <i> that really loved me</i>     
     <i> would have been upset.</i>    

704
00:43:19,931 --> 00:43:23,065
 Cooper:                        
 <i> She said, "I think you're</i>     
 <i> extremely inconsiderate to me</i> 

705
00:43:23,167 --> 00:43:25,467
        and I'm terribly hurt.  

706
00:43:25,570 --> 00:43:27,636
        You come to New York,   
        I have no idea why.     

707
00:43:27,738 --> 00:43:29,638
        You don't even call me."

708
00:43:36,447 --> 00:43:39,615
           Vanderbilt:          
      <i> I was very confused</i>      
        <i> about everything</i>       

709
00:43:39,717 --> 00:43:43,218
    <i> and she died soon after.</i>   

710
00:43:57,101 --> 00:43:59,868
     <i> And I went down there</i>     
          <i> to see her.</i>          

711
00:43:59,971 --> 00:44:03,271
           <i> Of course,</i>          
        <i> all her children</i>       
           <i> were there</i>          

712
00:44:03,373 --> 00:44:05,140
   <i> and relatives were there.</i>   

713
00:44:05,242 --> 00:44:09,444
          And they were         
        very cold to me,        
        with good reason.       

714
00:44:24,962 --> 00:44:27,229
             Cooper:            
    <i> I mean, there's so many</i>    
  <i> of those lost opportunities.</i> 

715
00:44:27,331 --> 00:44:29,932
       <i> I mean, you know,</i>       
       <i> she was raised by</i>       
       <i> her Aunt Gertrude,</i>      

716
00:44:30,034 --> 00:44:33,736
          <i> who created</i>          
      <i> the Whitney Museum,</i>      
   <i> who was an artist herself,</i>  

717
00:44:33,838 --> 00:44:38,707
   <i> who would have had so much</i>  
     <i> in common with my mom</i>     
      <i> had they connected.</i>      

718
00:44:38,809 --> 00:44:40,809
       It would have been       
 an extraordinary relationship, 

719
00:44:40,911 --> 00:44:44,647
  <i> but I don't think they ever</i>  
    <i> had a real conversation.</i>   

720
00:44:55,359 --> 00:44:57,392
           That face.           
           That face.           

721
00:44:57,494 --> 00:44:59,762
     - That beautiful face.     
      -<i> ( Cooper chuckles )</i>     

722
00:45:01,532 --> 00:45:05,801
    Well, that'll protect her   
      a little bit for now.     

723
00:45:05,903 --> 00:45:08,037
        ( both chuckle )        

724
00:45:08,139 --> 00:45:10,438
     - Just put it back on?     
     - Yeah.                    

725
00:45:14,511 --> 00:45:18,747
       Most of the things       
       in the dream boxes       
    I found in flea markets.    

726
00:45:23,754 --> 00:45:28,423
 <i> I did a dream box which I have</i>
     <i> in the fireplace room.</i>    

727
00:45:28,525 --> 00:45:32,427
   I found in the flea market   
      this extraordinary...     

728
00:45:35,232 --> 00:45:38,667
        they were written       
            in 1934.            

729
00:45:38,769 --> 00:45:41,136
        <i> They're all from</i>       
        <i> the same person</i>        

730
00:45:41,238 --> 00:45:43,005
          <i> and they're</i>          
       <i> crunched together</i>       

731
00:45:43,107 --> 00:45:46,842
        <i> and they're tied</i>       
    <i> very tightly with cord.</i>    

732
00:45:46,944 --> 00:45:48,777
         <i> I'm fascinated</i>        
        <i> by these letters</i>       

733
00:45:48,879 --> 00:45:52,715
       because part of me       
    really wants to read them   

734
00:45:52,817 --> 00:45:54,917
        and then another        
          part of me--          

735
00:45:55,019 --> 00:45:56,885
             I mean,            
       I'm not going to--       

736
00:45:56,987 --> 00:46:00,355
   <i> but there's a whole story</i>   
       <i> in those letters.</i>       

737
00:46:01,525 --> 00:46:03,391
    <i> And it's so interesting</i>    

738
00:46:03,493 --> 00:46:07,529
         <i> that it's just</i>        
      <i> exactly the same day</i>     
     <i> as the custody thing.</i>     

739
00:46:07,631 --> 00:46:09,531
       I mean, I made them      
        into a dream box.       

740
00:46:09,633 --> 00:46:13,335
  I didn't have to do anything  
    except get the Plexiglas    
         to put over it.        

741
00:46:18,976 --> 00:46:21,043
        Maybe they're not       
      love letters at all,      

742
00:46:21,145 --> 00:46:24,246
          but I somehow         
         think they are.        

743
00:46:26,751 --> 00:46:29,084
Cooper:                         
<i>Do you still think</i>              
<i>that the next great love--</i>      

744
00:46:29,186 --> 00:46:30,986
            Of course           
            it's gonna happen.  

745
00:46:31,088 --> 00:46:33,088
You think the next great love   
is right around the corner?     

746
00:46:33,190 --> 00:46:36,992
                    Absolutely. 
                    Absolutely. 

747
00:46:38,495 --> 00:46:40,362
Is there anyone I should        
know about right now?           

748
00:46:40,464 --> 00:46:42,998
                  <i> No.</i>          
                  <i> ( laughs )</i>   

749
00:46:43,100 --> 00:46:46,701
    I think Ben Brantley said   
     he's never met somebody    
       over the age of 16       

750
00:46:46,804 --> 00:46:49,371
     who loves being in love    
         as much as you.        

751
00:46:49,473 --> 00:46:52,274
           Vanderbilt:          
      <i> That's true. I think</i>     
  <i> we should always be in love.</i> 

752
00:46:55,512 --> 00:46:58,413
             Cooper:            
  <i> You had to go to Reno to get</i> 
    <i> a divorce from DiCicco.</i>    

753
00:46:58,515 --> 00:47:00,849
           Vanderbilt:          
     <i> I left him, you know,</i>     
            <i> finally.</i>           

754
00:47:00,951 --> 00:47:05,387
   <i> And then Leopold Stokowski</i>  
     <i> and I met at a party.</i>     

755
00:47:05,489 --> 00:47:09,391
        He obviously was        
    sort of smitten with me.    

756
00:47:09,493 --> 00:47:11,193
   And I couldn't believe it.   

757
00:47:11,295 --> 00:47:12,995
             I mean,            
       I was so flattered.      

758
00:47:13,097 --> 00:47:15,597
This is what he looked like     
when you first met him?         

759
00:47:16,901 --> 00:47:19,034
    Well, it's a terrible       
    photograph of him,          

760
00:47:19,136 --> 00:47:22,237
   but he was 63 when I first   
   met him and married him.     

761
00:47:25,075 --> 00:47:28,110
And was it something,           
like, as soon as you saw        
him, you thought--              

762
00:47:28,212 --> 00:47:29,878
           - Instant.           
            - Really?           

763
00:47:29,980 --> 00:47:32,380
       Knew him for a week      
       and married three        
       weeks later.             

764
00:47:32,482 --> 00:47:33,648
            - Really?           
            - Yeah.             

765
00:47:33,750 --> 00:47:35,417
      - I didn't know that.     
      - Yeah.                   

766
00:47:35,519 --> 00:47:37,519
       - How old were you?      
       - 20.                    

767
00:47:37,621 --> 00:47:40,789
         - You were 20?         
         And he was 63?         
          - Yeah. Yeah.         

768
00:47:40,891 --> 00:47:42,624
      Wow.                      

769
00:47:42,726 --> 00:47:44,827
Did any of your friends         
think it was weird?             

770
00:47:47,731 --> 00:47:51,233
        Uh, I don't know.       

771
00:47:51,335 --> 00:47:54,970
( laughs )                      
They didn't say anything?       

772
00:47:55,072 --> 00:47:57,206
      Didn't matter to me.      

773
00:47:57,308 --> 00:47:59,708
     I remember growing up,     
       I knew you had been      
         married to him,        

774
00:47:59,810 --> 00:48:02,811
- but I only knew him as the guy
who shook Mickey Mouse's hand.  
-<i> Yes, yeah.</i>                    

775
00:48:02,913 --> 00:48:05,613
        <i> 'Cause, I mean,</i>        
    <i> I think a lot of people</i>    
    <i> can't understand how...</i>    

776
00:48:05,716 --> 00:48:07,649
           Vanderbilt:          
       <i> I know they can't,</i>      
           <i> but it's--</i>          

777
00:48:07,751 --> 00:48:09,617
             Cooper:            
     <i> ...you would have been</i>    
       <i> attracted to him.</i>       

778
00:48:09,720 --> 00:48:12,787
           Vanderbilt:          
      <i> Well, I mean, having</i>     
       <i> come from DiCicco,</i>      

779
00:48:12,890 --> 00:48:14,923
     <i> who used to beat me up</i>    

780
00:48:15,025 --> 00:48:17,659
         and constantly         
          put me down,          

781
00:48:17,761 --> 00:48:21,997
            you know,           
      to have this genius,      
          which he was,         

782
00:48:22,099 --> 00:48:24,499
   <i> think I was extraordinary</i>   
         <i> and wonderful,</i>        

783
00:48:24,601 --> 00:48:27,202
         it just gave me        
      a big lift, you know?     

784
00:48:27,304 --> 00:48:29,804
       - Together.              
       -<i> ( woman coughs )</i>       

785
00:48:29,907 --> 00:48:31,974
             Shh, shh,          
             quiet, please.     

786
00:48:33,643 --> 00:48:35,010
                  Quiet.        

787
00:48:35,112 --> 00:48:36,979
     <i> ( orchestra playing )</i>     

788
00:48:37,081 --> 00:48:41,583
         Stan Stokowski:        
   <i> I think my mother admired</i>   
     <i> his art tremendously.</i>     

789
00:48:41,685 --> 00:48:43,252
            You know?           

790
00:48:43,354 --> 00:48:47,856
         And I was born         
         when he was 68.        

791
00:48:47,958 --> 00:48:49,791
        So-- and he lived       
            till 95.            

792
00:48:49,894 --> 00:48:54,329
     <i> And he was conducting</i>     
  <i> and recording till he died.</i>  

793
00:48:55,866 --> 00:48:58,666
       I wanted a father,       
     so I married Stokowski.    

794
00:49:02,139 --> 00:49:04,472
        And got a father        
       in a way, you know?      

795
00:49:04,574 --> 00:49:09,278
      <i> ( music continues )</i>      

796
00:49:09,380 --> 00:49:11,313
    Wait for the fortissimo.    

797
00:49:19,823 --> 00:49:22,291
           Stokowski:           
          <i> And I think</i>          
      <i> my father could see</i>      

798
00:49:22,393 --> 00:49:26,929
    <i> that she had incredible</i>    
    <i> insights into the world.</i>   

799
00:49:27,031 --> 00:49:30,665
    <i> Just the possibilities.</i>    
    <i> The fun of it, you know?</i>   

800
00:49:30,767 --> 00:49:33,635
     <i> I mean, my mom told me</i>    
       <i> a story about them</i>      

801
00:49:33,737 --> 00:49:36,004
        travelling across       
          the country,          

802
00:49:36,106 --> 00:49:38,840
     driving with a trailer     
          in the back.          

803
00:49:38,943 --> 00:49:42,945
     <i> It doesn't sound like</i>     
    <i> anything they would do.</i>    

804
00:49:48,685 --> 00:49:52,120
           Vanderbilt:          
      <i> And we were together</i>     
       <i> for over 12 years.</i>      

805
00:49:54,091 --> 00:49:57,559
           Like this.           
     We saw very few people,    
            you know?           

806
00:49:57,661 --> 00:50:01,563
           I just was           
        at every concert        
            backstage           

807
00:50:01,665 --> 00:50:03,999
    <i> helping him get dressed</i>    
         <i> and all that.</i>         

808
00:50:04,101 --> 00:50:05,367
             Cooper:            
      <i> So you would travel</i>      
           <i> with him?</i>           

809
00:50:05,469 --> 00:50:06,901
           Vanderbilt:          
        <i> Oh, yeah. Yeah.</i>        

810
00:50:11,175 --> 00:50:13,541
     It sounds like they had    
      a good life together      

811
00:50:13,643 --> 00:50:16,544
    while they were together.   

812
00:50:16,646 --> 00:50:19,614
           Vanderbilt:          
   <i> But when the children came</i>  
         <i> and he toured,</i>        

813
00:50:19,716 --> 00:50:22,650
      I didn't go with him.     
  I stayed, you know, at home.  

814
00:50:22,752 --> 00:50:25,820
        But it was a very       
     kind of isolated life,     

815
00:50:25,922 --> 00:50:28,290
      and I was, you know,      
      in my young 20s then      

816
00:50:28,392 --> 00:50:31,726
      <i> and it was difficult</i>     
      <i> in a certain sense.</i>      

817
00:50:31,828 --> 00:50:35,697
       <i> So I had Dodo come</i>      
    <i> and live with us there.</i>    

818
00:50:35,799 --> 00:50:37,699
     - Cooper:<i> How was that?</i>    
     - It was heaven.           

819
00:50:37,801 --> 00:50:41,069
    Getting your mommy back.    

820
00:50:41,171 --> 00:50:43,205
  - Cooper:<i> You met Dodo? Wow.</i>  
  - Stokowski:<i> Yeah.</i>            

821
00:50:43,307 --> 00:50:45,974
   She was like the paintings   
     that my mom did of her.    

822
00:50:46,076 --> 00:50:48,010
      She was a big person.     

823
00:50:48,112 --> 00:50:49,844
            You know,           
     a big sort of presence.    

824
00:50:49,946 --> 00:50:52,047
          <i> Very gentle,</i>         
          <i> very sweet,</i>          

825
00:50:52,149 --> 00:50:55,384
       and very obviously       
           interested           

826
00:50:55,486 --> 00:50:58,987
        - in us, in Mom.        
        - Hmm.                  

827
00:50:59,089 --> 00:51:02,157
           Vanderbilt:          
   <i> I mean, I think Stokowski</i>   
     <i> loved Stan and Chris,</i>     

828
00:51:02,259 --> 00:51:05,260
      <i> but he was not meant</i>     
        <i> to be a father.</i>        

829
00:51:05,362 --> 00:51:07,129
            He wasn't           
       the kind of person       

830
00:51:07,231 --> 00:51:09,364
      that you'd bond with,     
      you know what I mean?     

831
00:51:16,173 --> 00:51:18,106
             Cooper:            
     <i> I think my mom always</i>     
       <i> dreamed of having</i>       

832
00:51:18,208 --> 00:51:22,610
     <i> sort of a little house</i>    
       <i> and a white picket</i>      
         <i> fence family.</i>         

833
00:51:22,712 --> 00:51:27,282
    And that kind of vision,    
     that's what she wanted     
         her life to be.        

834
00:51:27,384 --> 00:51:29,717
        <i> But in reality,</i>        
       <i> she has this drive</i>      

835
00:51:29,819 --> 00:51:32,387
 <i> and she has this determination</i>
   <i> to propel herself forward.</i>  

836
00:51:32,489 --> 00:51:36,491
         And that drive         
   makes it impossible to have  
     that white picket fence    

837
00:51:36,593 --> 00:51:37,859
           and to have          
        that family life        

838
00:51:37,961 --> 00:51:41,896
     and to have, you know,     
        a calm existence.       

839
00:51:41,998 --> 00:51:46,034
           Vanderbilt:          
     <i> Well, I wanted to make</i>    
     <i> my mark, so to speak.</i>     

840
00:51:46,136 --> 00:51:51,039
 And the most mark one can make 
       is to be an actress      

841
00:51:51,141 --> 00:51:55,143
        <i> because you get</i>        
       <i> the most exposure.</i>      

842
00:51:55,245 --> 00:51:58,012
        <i> So I think that</i>        
        <i> was a great part</i>       

843
00:51:58,115 --> 00:52:00,648
     <i> of my wanting to act.</i>     

844
00:52:00,750 --> 00:52:04,886
         <i> And I also had</i>        
   <i> a very subjective feeling</i>   

845
00:52:04,988 --> 00:52:08,723
        that in each part       
          I would find          

846
00:52:08,825 --> 00:52:11,293
         part of myself,        

847
00:52:11,395 --> 00:52:15,063
      <i> which would make me</i>      
   <i> feel better about myself.</i>   

848
00:52:15,165 --> 00:52:17,065
          <i> ( applause )</i>         

849
00:52:20,504 --> 00:52:22,604
           Stokowski:           
   <i> One of the reasons I think</i>  

850
00:52:22,706 --> 00:52:25,373
        that they perhaps       
        had disagreement        

851
00:52:25,476 --> 00:52:29,444
       was because he was       
    a little bit discouraging   
      of her doing acting.      

852
00:52:29,546 --> 00:52:33,115
   <i> I think perhaps he didn't</i>   
   <i> consider it as high an art</i>  

853
00:52:33,217 --> 00:52:35,883
     <i> as she was capable of.</i>    

854
00:52:37,954 --> 00:52:39,687
           Vanderbilt:          
       <i> You know, he wrote</i>      
          <i> me a letter</i>          

855
00:52:39,789 --> 00:52:41,990
     <i> and he said don't let</i>     
    <i> "Vanity Fair" fool you.</i>    

856
00:52:42,092 --> 00:52:46,461
    <i> Your real talent is your</i>   
    <i> painting and you should</i>    
      <i> concentrate on that.</i>     

857
00:52:46,563 --> 00:52:50,632
  <i> And don't think that parties</i> 
    <i> and people you're seeing</i>   

858
00:52:50,734 --> 00:52:55,837
        <i> and social life</i>        
   <i> and all that is important,</i>  
       <i> because it's not.</i>       

859
00:52:58,542 --> 00:53:00,208
             Cooper:            
    <i> A lot of people, though,</i>   
      <i> who had been through</i>     

860
00:53:00,310 --> 00:53:03,077
 <i> what you went through early on</i>
      <i> would not have done</i>      

861
00:53:03,180 --> 00:53:05,180
       <i> something that was</i>      
       <i> in the public eye.</i>      

862
00:53:05,282 --> 00:53:07,749
    They might have retreated   
      from the public eye.      

863
00:53:07,851 --> 00:53:11,186
       Well, I didn't want      
           to do that.          

864
00:53:11,288 --> 00:53:13,622
  <i> Because I have the same name</i> 
         <i> as my mother,</i>         

865
00:53:13,723 --> 00:53:16,090
   <i> I thought if I could make</i>   
     <i> something of my life,</i>     

866
00:53:16,193 --> 00:53:20,162
    it would make her sort of   
  a wonderful mother, you know? 

867
00:53:20,264 --> 00:53:22,964
        I mean, it would        
      reflect well on her.      

868
00:53:23,066 --> 00:53:24,799
          Why was that          
        important to you?       

869
00:53:24,901 --> 00:53:26,801
       She was my mother,       
            you know?           

870
00:53:26,903 --> 00:53:31,072
You said you stopped            
communicating with her          

871
00:53:31,175 --> 00:53:33,542
from the time                   
when you were 20                
to the time you were 38?        

872
00:53:33,644 --> 00:53:35,410
       - Yes.                   
       - Why did you stop       
       communicating?           

873
00:53:35,512 --> 00:53:37,011
           Because of Stokowski.

874
00:53:37,113 --> 00:53:40,248
    Because then was the time   
 for me to start supporting her 

875
00:53:40,350 --> 00:53:43,084
  because I inherited my money  
         when I was 21.         

876
00:53:43,187 --> 00:53:46,321
  Because I thought he was god, 
        that's what I did       

877
00:53:46,423 --> 00:53:48,723
      and I didn't give her     
        any money at all.       

878
00:53:51,094 --> 00:53:54,462
     <i> Stokowski kept saying</i>     
      <i> she never loved you.</i>     

879
00:53:54,565 --> 00:53:56,531
     <i> Why should you do it?</i>     

880
00:54:00,637 --> 00:54:03,371
      <i> There was a terrible</i>     
     <i> sort of press about it</i>    

881
00:54:03,473 --> 00:54:05,273
         <i> in the papers</i>         
          <i> and all that</i>         

882
00:54:05,375 --> 00:54:07,375
           that I was           
      cutting my mother off     
        without anything.       

883
00:54:07,477 --> 00:54:11,613
        <i> You know, darling,</i>     
        <i> so many of our friends</i> 
        <i> have asked us</i>          

884
00:54:11,715 --> 00:54:15,217
         why did we ever choose 
         the doll business      
         to go into.            

885
00:54:15,319 --> 00:54:18,286
Well, you know,                 
darling, ever since             
we were little kids,            

886
00:54:18,388 --> 00:54:19,987
we used to love                 
to play with dolls              

887
00:54:20,090 --> 00:54:22,557
 and make dolls' dresses        
and all sorts of things.        

888
00:54:22,659 --> 00:54:25,893
And, you know,                  
with the income tax             
the way it is nowadays,         

889
00:54:25,995 --> 00:54:27,729
well, I think everybody's       
got to go to work.              

890
00:54:27,831 --> 00:54:29,797
    - Don't you think so?       
    - Oh, how right you are.    

891
00:54:29,933 --> 00:54:31,833
         There.                 

892
00:54:31,935 --> 00:54:35,036
      Thank you, everybody.     
      Good-bye.                 

893
00:54:38,975 --> 00:54:41,209
     - Vanderbilt: This goes    
     way, way back.             
     - Cooper: Wow.             

894
00:54:41,311 --> 00:54:43,345
          This is Stan.         

895
00:54:43,447 --> 00:54:45,480
         This is when I was     
         living in Greenwich.   

896
00:54:45,582 --> 00:54:47,515
  Wow.                          

897
00:54:49,986 --> 00:54:52,287
           - So 1952?           
           - Yeah.              

898
00:54:52,389 --> 00:54:55,123
It's a great picture.           
You were 28 here.               

899
00:54:55,225 --> 00:54:57,659
           Just about           
           to blow the coop.    

900
00:54:57,761 --> 00:54:59,494
( laughs )                      
What? What do you mean?         

901
00:54:59,596 --> 00:55:03,265
   Well, I knew                 
   that I wasn't going          
   to stay married to Leopold.  

902
00:55:03,367 --> 00:55:04,899
Oh, really?                     

903
00:55:05,001 --> 00:55:09,971
   That's when I met Sinatra,   
   after I had done that play.  

904
00:55:10,073 --> 00:55:14,542
        <i>  Two drifters </i>       

905
00:55:14,645 --> 00:55:18,846
    <i>  Off to see the world </i>   

906
00:55:18,948 --> 00:55:23,785
         <i>  There's such</i>        
        <i> a lot of world </i>       

907
00:55:23,887 --> 00:55:26,954
         <i>  To see... </i>         

908
00:55:27,056 --> 00:55:29,991
           Vanderbilt:          
  <i> Because Sinatra was in love</i>  
     <i> with me and behind me,</i>    

909
00:55:30,093 --> 00:55:33,295
       I could leave god,       
          so to speak.          

910
00:55:33,397 --> 00:55:36,331
       <i> And I took my kids</i>      
       <i> and I walked out.</i>       

911
00:55:36,433 --> 00:55:38,400
    <i> And I was able to do it.</i>   

912
00:55:40,570 --> 00:55:43,204
    <i> And even though I didn't</i>   
     <i> for one minute believe</i>    

913
00:55:43,307 --> 00:55:45,907
  <i> we were going to go swinging</i> 
     <i> down the lane together</i>    

914
00:55:46,009 --> 00:55:48,476
   <i> for the rest of our lives,</i>  
          <i> I used that.</i>         

915
00:55:48,578 --> 00:55:52,947
   <i>  My huckleberry friend </i>   

916
00:55:53,049 --> 00:55:57,352
       <i>  Moon river... </i>       

917
00:55:57,454 --> 00:56:00,622
   - Cooper:                    
   <i> There was a custody trial.</i>  
   - Vanderbilt:<i> Yes.</i>           

918
00:56:00,724 --> 00:56:02,390
        <i> Well, of course,</i>       
        <i> it's Stokowski.</i>        

919
00:56:02,492 --> 00:56:04,826
   <i> He never thought I'd have</i>   
     <i> the guts to fight it.</i>     

920
00:56:04,928 --> 00:56:07,629
             <i> Ever.</i>             
       <i> But I've got guts.</i>      

921
00:56:09,366 --> 00:56:11,299
         <i> And I won it.</i>         

922
00:56:13,870 --> 00:56:16,037
           Stokowski:           
  <i> It was a bit of a strange--</i>  

923
00:56:16,139 --> 00:56:17,939
        <i> you know, it had</i>       
    <i> some strange atmospheres</i>   

924
00:56:18,041 --> 00:56:20,174
          <i> because two</i>          
      <i> different households</i>     

925
00:56:20,276 --> 00:56:24,779
       and my mom and dad       
  weren't really getting along  

926
00:56:24,881 --> 00:56:27,382
     very well at that time.    

927
00:56:29,486 --> 00:56:32,053
             Cooper:            
   <i> Was the divorce difficult</i>   
      <i> for Stan and Chris?</i>      

928
00:56:32,121 --> 00:56:34,356
         I think it was.        

929
00:56:34,458 --> 00:56:38,827
       And I think it was       
      because I didn't talk     
    to them enough about it.    

930
00:56:41,965 --> 00:56:44,098
           Stokowski:           
     <i> Sometimes when my mom</i>     
           <i> described</i>           

931
00:56:44,200 --> 00:56:46,133
        <i> her relationship</i>       
        <i> with her mother</i>        

932
00:56:46,236 --> 00:56:50,438
     <i> about how she appeared</i>    
 <i> sort of as a beautiful figure</i> 
           <i> sometimes,</i>          

933
00:56:50,540 --> 00:56:53,742
  I remember feeling that       
  with my mom, too,             

934
00:56:53,844 --> 00:56:58,613
  because she was busy          
  doing lots of things          

935
00:56:58,715 --> 00:57:02,617
and involved in, you know,      
theatrical pursuits,            

936
00:57:02,719 --> 00:57:04,719
<i>and painting</i>                    
<i>was always there.</i>               

937
00:57:04,821 --> 00:57:08,623
    I do remember               
    that feeling                

938
00:57:08,725 --> 00:57:12,427
   <i> of her being a little bit</i>   
          <i> more distant</i>         

939
00:57:12,529 --> 00:57:15,663
       <i> than I would have</i>       
       <i> wanted her to be.</i>       

940
00:57:17,267 --> 00:57:19,333
     <i> But I think that's how</i>    
     <i> her mother was to her</i>     

941
00:57:19,436 --> 00:57:21,235
and it was a natural thing.     

942
00:57:21,337 --> 00:57:24,839
And over the years,             
