1133
01:07:43,659 --> 01:07:44,658
              Yes.              

1134
01:07:44,760 --> 01:07:47,328
        My mom and Sidney       
            separated           

1135
01:07:47,430 --> 01:07:50,131
          and divorced          
      when I was about 12.      

1136
01:07:50,233 --> 01:07:54,935
       That was difficult       
       for me, of course,       

1137
01:07:55,038 --> 01:07:57,238
     but on the other hand,     

1138
01:07:57,340 --> 01:07:59,573
      I could see how happy     
           my mom was.          

1139
01:08:02,078 --> 01:08:05,279
           Vanderbilt:          
       <i> I had an awful lot</i>      
     <i> to work out in my life</i>    

1140
01:08:05,381 --> 01:08:09,016
 <i> and it took me years and years</i>
   <i> and years to work it out.</i>   

1141
01:08:12,855 --> 01:08:16,490
   <i> But when I married Wyatt,</i>   
    <i> I knew it was for life.</i>    

1142
01:08:17,793 --> 01:08:19,193
             Cooper:            
       <i> My dad wanted you</i>       

1143
01:08:19,295 --> 01:08:20,928
     <i> to reestablish contact</i>    
         <i> with your mom?</i>        

1144
01:08:21,030 --> 01:08:24,031
           Yes, he was          
      a great help in that.     

1145
01:08:36,912 --> 01:08:40,614
  She then had something called 
      hysterical blindness      

1146
01:08:40,716 --> 01:08:43,451
     which you're not blind,    
          but you're--          

1147
01:08:43,553 --> 01:08:47,221
         psychologically        
        something happens       
     so that you can't see.     

1148
01:08:49,024 --> 01:08:51,225
    <i> I felt why was I afraid</i>    

1149
01:08:51,327 --> 01:08:55,496
      <i> of this sad person,</i>      
           <i> you know?</i>           

1150
01:08:55,598 --> 01:08:57,565
       Who was so gentle.       

1151
01:08:57,666 --> 01:09:01,435
      I mean, she was like      
     a butterfly, you know?     

1152
01:09:04,140 --> 01:09:06,640
           Stokowski:           
      <i> When Mom's mother--</i>      

1153
01:09:06,742 --> 01:09:11,112
  <i> for the first time I met her</i> 
      <i> when I was 13 or 14,</i>     

1154
01:09:11,214 --> 01:09:14,415
      <i> and just she visited</i>     
    <i> and I thought to myself,</i>   

1155
01:09:14,517 --> 01:09:16,049
       "Wow, this is            
      my grandmother            

1156
01:09:16,185 --> 01:09:17,918
 and this is the first time     
 I'm meeting her."              

1157
01:09:18,020 --> 01:09:20,053
        So when she reconnected 
        with her mother,        

1158
01:09:20,156 --> 01:09:22,523
  that's when you met her mother
  for the first time?           

1159
01:09:22,625 --> 01:09:24,592
       - Yeah.                  
       - Do you remember        
       what she was like?       

1160
01:09:24,693 --> 01:09:27,228
 She was very sort of           
 formally dressed               

1161
01:09:27,330 --> 01:09:31,465
 and very prim                  
 and slightly reserved.         

1162
01:09:33,736 --> 01:09:36,203
         <i> We didn't have</i>        
       <i> much conversation,</i>      

1163
01:09:36,305 --> 01:09:40,474
 but I knew that it was         
 an important event.            

1164
01:09:40,576 --> 01:09:43,910
           Vanderbilt:          
 <i> We went into my studio and...</i> 

1165
01:09:45,814 --> 01:09:50,284
      we really didn't talk     
         about anything         

1166
01:09:50,386 --> 01:09:53,354
        except chitchat,        
            you know?           

1167
01:09:55,057 --> 01:09:57,824
        Which, of course,       
          I regret now.         

1168
01:10:01,297 --> 01:10:05,666
     <i> She died the day after</i>    
        <i> Carter was born.</i>       

1169
01:10:05,768 --> 01:10:07,834
   <i> And the last time I spoke</i>   
      <i> to her on the phone</i>      

1170
01:10:07,936 --> 01:10:10,371
      was just a few hours      
       after he was born.       

1171
01:10:10,473 --> 01:10:12,706
         And, of course,        
         I wanted a girl        

1172
01:10:12,808 --> 01:10:15,509
    <i> and I was gonna tell her</i>   
  <i> I was gonna call her Gloria.</i> 

1173
01:10:15,611 --> 01:10:18,646
          <i> I almost was</i>         
      <i> going to lie to her</i>      
   <i> and tell her it was a girl</i>  

1174
01:10:18,747 --> 01:10:21,348
  <i> because I knew that she was</i>  
     <i> so ill, but I didn't.</i>     

1175
01:10:21,450 --> 01:10:25,018
      And when I told her,      
            she said,           

1176
01:10:25,120 --> 01:10:27,821
    "Oh, Gloria, you're gonna   
     start a baseball team."    

1177
01:10:27,923 --> 01:10:30,357
           ( laughs )           

1178
01:10:30,459 --> 01:10:32,893
           Those were           
      her last words to me.     

1179
01:11:09,332 --> 01:11:11,665
           Vanderbilt:          
  <i> One night before I was going</i> 
     <i> to escape, I thought,</i>     

1180
01:11:11,767 --> 01:11:15,636
      <i> "I'm going to count</i>      
    <i> all the terrible regrets</i>   
     <i> of my life, you know,</i>     

1181
01:11:15,738 --> 01:11:18,239
      <i> 'cause now I'm able</i>      
         <i> to face them."</i>        

1182
01:11:18,341 --> 01:11:21,742
      So I started to count     
      my regrets, you know?     

1183
01:11:23,178 --> 01:11:25,412
        <i> It was not easy.</i>       

1184
01:11:27,015 --> 01:11:28,982
             Cooper:            
         <i> You don't want</i>        
        <i> to go into them?</i>       

1185
01:11:29,084 --> 01:11:33,053
    Well, my greatest regret    
   is that I wasn't with Dodo   
         when she died.         

1186
01:11:38,427 --> 01:11:40,427
    <i> When I left Stokowski...</i>   

1187
01:11:42,498 --> 01:11:45,899
     <i> there were things that</i>    
    <i> were happening so fast,</i>    
           <i> you know?</i>           

1188
01:11:46,001 --> 01:11:50,937
         <i> And I kind of</i>         
        <i> lost her again.</i>        

1189
01:11:52,308 --> 01:11:54,808
         <i> But she never</i>         
        <i> stopped writing.</i>       

1190
01:11:57,780 --> 01:12:00,847
            <i> And then</i>           
     <i> the last letter I got,</i>    

1191
01:12:00,949 --> 01:12:03,317
     which was typewritten,     

1192
01:12:03,419 --> 01:12:05,952
         was to say that        
     she had died, you know?    

1193
01:12:12,762 --> 01:12:14,495
             Cooper:            
       <i> Where did she die?</i>      

1194
01:12:14,597 --> 01:12:15,929
      <i> Or do you know when?</i>     

1195
01:12:16,031 --> 01:12:18,098
           Vanderbilt:          
    <i> With Catholic Charities.</i>   

1196
01:12:20,569 --> 01:12:22,536
        And I regret that       
           very much.           

1197
01:12:22,638 --> 01:12:24,871
             And...             

1198
01:12:24,973 --> 01:12:27,107
        <i> she was with me</i>        
        <i> when I was born</i>        

1199
01:12:27,209 --> 01:12:30,411
        <i> and I would like</i>       
     <i> to have been with her</i>     
    <i> when she died, you know?</i>   

1200
01:12:53,068 --> 01:12:55,936
  <i> Nothing is the way we think</i>  
       <i> it's going to be.</i>       

1201
01:12:56,038 --> 01:12:58,572
     <i> It really isn't ever.</i>     

1202
01:12:58,674 --> 01:13:00,674
             Cooper:            
      <i> You know, one thing</i>      
         <i> she said to me</i>        

1203
01:13:00,776 --> 01:13:04,645
       is that she's never      
    had a plan for her life,    
   which I just find amazing.   

1204
01:13:04,747 --> 01:13:08,014
        It's kind of like       
       walking a tightrope      

1205
01:13:08,116 --> 01:13:09,916
          all the time.         

1206
01:13:10,018 --> 01:13:12,653
    And then you have to stay   
        on the tightrope        

1207
01:13:12,755 --> 01:13:16,490
     so you don't fall off,     
            you know?           

1208
01:13:18,994 --> 01:13:21,595
             Cooper:            
     <i> And so my dad brought</i>     
     <i> something to the table</i>    

1209
01:13:21,697 --> 01:13:23,564
        <i> that she hadn't</i>        
      <i> experienced before.</i>      

1210
01:13:23,666 --> 01:13:27,000
      I mean, he had a plan     
     for what a family life     
      was going to be like      

1211
01:13:27,102 --> 01:13:28,836
    and what they were going    
     to be like as parents.     

1212
01:13:28,937 --> 01:13:32,939
  <i> I think that was a big part</i>  
   <i> of the appeal for my mom.</i>   

1213
01:13:33,041 --> 01:13:34,775
    It's interesting because    
    they could not have been    

1214
01:13:34,877 --> 01:13:36,810
   from more different worlds,  
            you know?           

1215
01:13:36,912 --> 01:13:40,981
          <i> My dad came</i>          
   <i> from this relatively poor</i>   
     <i> family in Mississippi,</i>    

1216
01:13:41,083 --> 01:13:43,884
        <i> had two parents</i>        
   <i> for most of his childhood</i>   

1217
01:13:43,986 --> 01:13:46,453
    <i> and brothers and sisters</i>   
    <i> and had family reunions,</i>   

1218
01:13:46,555 --> 01:13:48,955
         <i> and relatives</i>         
        <i> were all around.</i>       

1219
01:13:49,057 --> 01:13:50,791
          Man on radio:         
        <i> You're listening</i>       
        <i> to Wyatt Cooper</i>        

1220
01:13:50,893 --> 01:13:52,259
          <i> reminiscing</i>          
       <i> with Charles Ruas</i>       
           <i> about life</i>          

1221
01:13:52,361 --> 01:13:54,127
        <i> within a large,</i>        
     <i> rural Southern family.</i>    

1222
01:13:54,229 --> 01:13:55,996
             Wyatt:             
       <i> These were joyous</i>       
       <i> occasions for me.</i>       

1223
01:13:56,098 --> 01:13:58,565
   <i> To see all those colorful</i>   
     <i> people of such variety</i>    

1224
01:13:58,667 --> 01:14:00,868
    <i> gathered in holiday mood</i>   
        <i> with their jokes</i>       

1225
01:14:00,969 --> 01:14:03,404
       <i> and their laughter</i>      
     <i> and their familiarity</i>     
        <i> with each other</i>        

1226
01:14:03,506 --> 01:14:05,639
      <i> was exciting a thing</i>     
           <i> as I knew.</i>          

1227
01:14:05,741 --> 01:14:08,742
      <i> They belonged to me</i>      
       <i> and we had claims</i>       
        <i> on one another.</i>        

1228
01:14:08,844 --> 01:14:11,378
     Sort of scary in a way     
   'cause I'm kind of a loner.  

1229
01:14:11,480 --> 01:14:15,215
     <i> But I've had to learn</i>     
     <i> to belong to a family.</i>    

1230
01:14:16,685 --> 01:14:18,786
           Stokowski:           
       <i> Wyatt brought that</i>      

1231
01:14:18,888 --> 01:14:23,023
     <i> kind of gentle feeling</i>    
           <i> of family.</i>          

1232
01:14:23,125 --> 01:14:25,959
          And they were         
       having their kids,       

1233
01:14:26,061 --> 01:14:29,362
         <i> so I did feel</i>         
          <i> a little bit</i>         

1234
01:14:29,465 --> 01:14:33,534
  like it was a new generation, 
          which it was.         

1235
01:14:35,471 --> 01:14:38,572
            <i> I was 16</i>           
    <i> when Anderson was born.</i>    

1236
01:14:38,674 --> 01:14:43,343
   <i> There wasn't enough time,</i>   
     <i> really, for us to all</i>     
          <i> be together.</i>         

1237
01:14:43,446 --> 01:14:48,081
        <i> So it felt like</i>        
     <i> two different families</i>    
       <i> in a lot of ways.</i>       

1238
01:14:53,489 --> 01:14:55,188
             Cooper:            
         <i> I think my dad</i>        
         <i> helped my mom</i>         

1239
01:14:55,290 --> 01:14:57,090
      <i> learn what a parent</i>      
       <i> was supposed to do</i>      

1240
01:14:57,192 --> 01:15:00,393
  <i> and see what a relationship</i>  
  <i> with children could be like.</i> 

1241
01:15:00,496 --> 01:15:02,262
           Vanderbilt:          
      <i> When you were born,</i>      

1242
01:15:02,364 --> 01:15:04,230
        I was sure it was       
        gonna be a girl.        

1243
01:15:04,333 --> 01:15:06,199
           Vanderbilt:          
   <i> You really wanted a girl?</i>   

1244
01:15:06,301 --> 01:15:08,068
          - Oh!                 
          -<i> ( laughs )</i>          

1245
01:15:08,170 --> 01:15:10,771
           I was meant          
       to have daughters.       

1246
01:15:10,873 --> 01:15:12,305
         I won't take it        
           personally.          

1247
01:15:12,407 --> 01:15:14,174
           <i> There was</i>           
        <i> a fertility drug</i>       

1248
01:15:14,276 --> 01:15:18,411
  which was then illegal to get 
      in the United States.     

1249
01:15:18,514 --> 01:15:21,949
       <i> And I went to Oona</i>      
  <i> and Charlie's in Switzerland</i> 

1250
01:15:22,050 --> 01:15:24,618
     <i> and a friend from Rome</i>    
        <i> brought it there</i>       

1251
01:15:24,720 --> 01:15:27,253
   and then we all strapped it  
      to me before I got--      

1252
01:15:27,356 --> 01:15:29,990
    Oona and Charlie Chaplin    
  helped strap drugs to your--  

1253
01:15:30,092 --> 01:15:31,658
        <i> Yes, to my body.</i>       

1254
01:15:31,760 --> 01:15:35,496
  <i> Anyway, suddenly, you know,</i>  
      <i> for the first time,</i>      

1255
01:15:35,598 --> 01:15:38,532
    <i> I had a family, really.</i>    

1256
01:15:49,011 --> 01:15:51,144
             Cooper:            
 <i> There was a conscious decision</i>
        <i> of you and Daddy</i>       

1257
01:15:51,246 --> 01:15:53,313
    <i> to include us on things?</i>   

1258
01:15:53,415 --> 01:15:55,782
           Vanderbilt:          
    <i> Well, it never occurred</i>    
  <i> that we wouldn't, you know?</i>  

1259
01:15:55,885 --> 01:15:59,019
        I mean, you were        
     included in everything     
       from the beginning.      

1260
01:16:01,824 --> 01:16:03,924
             Wyatt:             
      <i> I think that we can</i>      
      <i> involve our children</i>     

1261
01:16:04,026 --> 01:16:05,959
           <i> much more</i>           
       <i> in our own lives.</i>       

1262
01:16:06,061 --> 01:16:07,528
          <i> If somebody</i>          
        <i> is coming over,</i>        

1263
01:16:07,630 --> 01:16:09,362
       <i> my kids meet them</i>       
      <i> and talk with them.</i>      

1264
01:16:09,464 --> 01:16:13,000
   <i> And then I encourage them</i>   
 <i> to express opinions afterward</i> 

1265
01:16:13,101 --> 01:16:15,903
        <i> about the adults</i>       
   <i> because one of the things</i>   

1266
01:16:16,005 --> 01:16:18,805
      <i> that's so beneficial</i>     
     <i> in the extended family</i>    

1267
01:16:18,908 --> 01:16:20,707
       <i> is that there was</i>       
     <i> such diversity in it.</i>     

1268
01:16:20,809 --> 01:16:22,576
    <i> There's the family drunk</i>   

1269
01:16:22,678 --> 01:16:24,277
     <i> and there's the uncle</i>     
        <i> who's very rich</i>        

1270
01:16:24,379 --> 01:16:26,346
        <i> and then the one</i>       
       <i> who's always poor.</i>      

1271
01:16:26,448 --> 01:16:29,983
          <i> So you learn</i>         
   <i> that there are many kinds</i>   
    <i> of people in the world.</i>    

1272
01:16:31,921 --> 01:16:34,154
          Truman Capote         
    and Charlie Chaplin came    

1273
01:16:34,256 --> 01:16:36,990
         <i> and, you know,</i>        
    <i> it was all these people</i>    
        <i> I saw in movies</i>        

1274
01:16:37,092 --> 01:16:40,561
     <i> and saw on television</i>     
   <i> and we were always sitting</i>  
       <i> next to the people</i>      

1275
01:16:40,663 --> 01:16:43,096
          <i> and we were</i>          
      <i> to make conversation</i>     

1276
01:16:43,198 --> 01:16:46,700
   and considered on equal par  
      with everybody else.      

1277
01:16:48,136 --> 01:16:50,203
      <i> My dad wrote a book</i>      
       <i> called "Families."</i>      

1278
01:16:50,305 --> 01:16:52,873
      <i> He really wrote it,</i>      
      <i> I think, as a letter</i>     
      <i> to my brother and I.</i>     

1279
01:16:52,975 --> 01:16:55,809
        And he wrote it,        
            I think,            

1280
01:16:55,911 --> 01:16:58,745
     because he didn't know     
      if he would be around     

1281
01:16:58,847 --> 01:17:02,849
       and he wanted there      
         to be something        

1282
01:17:02,952 --> 01:17:06,887
      that my brother and I     
      could read and go to      

1283
01:17:06,989 --> 01:17:10,857
         as we got older        
   and sort of hear his voice.  

1284
01:17:10,960 --> 01:17:14,094
             Wyatt:             
          <i> I see myself</i>         
        <i> in my two sons,</i>        

1285
01:17:14,196 --> 01:17:17,998
 <i> in their youth, their promise,</i>
      <i> their possibilities.</i>     

1286
01:17:18,100 --> 01:17:21,234
      <i> I hear those tender</i>      
    <i> and stalwart little men</i>    

1287
01:17:21,336 --> 01:17:25,538
  <i> asking the questions I asked</i> 
      <i> and am still asking.</i>     

1288
01:17:25,641 --> 01:17:27,474
             Cooper:            
         <i> I didn't know</i>         
        <i> my dad was sick.</i>       

1289
01:17:27,576 --> 01:17:30,978
  <i> I just remember one instance</i> 
 <i> where he was lifting some bags</i>

1290
01:17:31,080 --> 01:17:34,982
     and my mom got annoyed     
   that we weren't helping him  
         lift the bags.         

1291
01:17:35,084 --> 01:17:37,784
 And it was the first indication
I got that there was something--

1292
01:17:37,886 --> 01:17:39,285
  some sort of physical thing.  

1293
01:17:39,387 --> 01:17:41,688
           <i> He had had</i>          
        <i> a heart attack.</i>        

1294
01:17:41,790 --> 01:17:44,390
         <i> Heart disease</i>         
       <i> was in his family.</i>      

1295
01:17:44,493 --> 01:17:47,460
         <i> But it wasn't</i>         
         <i> until I was 10</i>        

1296
01:17:47,562 --> 01:17:49,195
    <i> and it was right before</i>    
          <i> Christmas--</i>          

1297
01:17:49,297 --> 01:17:51,431
         so it had been         
        December of '77--       

1298
01:17:51,533 --> 01:17:53,133
    he went to the hospital.    

1299
01:17:53,235 --> 01:17:56,503
         And at the time        
         they had a rule        

1300
01:17:56,605 --> 01:17:58,839
    that kids weren't allowed   
     to go to ICU to visit.     

1301
01:17:58,941 --> 01:18:01,108
         <i> At some point</i>         
    <i> we were kind of snuck in</i>   

1302
01:18:01,209 --> 01:18:04,878
    <i> because I think somebody</i>   
      <i> realized that things</i>     
      <i> weren't going well.</i>      

1303
01:18:04,980 --> 01:18:07,147
 And I remember just seeing him 
      once in the hospital.     

1304
01:18:07,249 --> 01:18:08,782
           And I hated          
      seeing him like that.     

1305
01:18:08,884 --> 01:18:11,518
   I hated sort of seeing him   
      in a weakened state.      

1306
01:18:11,620 --> 01:18:14,688
       He said to me that       
     he'd like to be buried     

1307
01:18:14,790 --> 01:18:16,857
              in...             

1308
01:18:20,663 --> 01:18:22,863
            you know,           
         where my family        
           was buried           

1309
01:18:22,965 --> 01:18:25,365
  because it was near New York  
         and you could--        

1310
01:18:25,467 --> 01:18:28,334
   we could go and visit him,   
           the grave.           

1311
01:18:30,039 --> 01:18:32,472
           And I said,          
