01:29:45,613 --> 01:29:49,114
   and you can't prevent them   
         from happening.        

1499
01:29:50,752 --> 01:29:52,552
      <i> We met at Princeton.</i>     

1500
01:29:52,654 --> 01:29:55,388
    <i> You know, I had a crush</i>    
       <i> on him from afar.</i>       

1501
01:29:55,490 --> 01:29:59,158
      <i> But the spring term</i>      
       <i> of my senior year,</i>      

1502
01:29:59,260 --> 01:30:01,227
      <i> we started spending</i>      
         <i> time together.</i>        

1503
01:30:08,636 --> 01:30:11,971
   <i> Then the last few months,</i>   

1504
01:30:12,073 --> 01:30:14,607
         I just remember        
          Carter's mood         

1505
01:30:14,709 --> 01:30:17,810
         getting darker.        

1506
01:30:17,912 --> 01:30:22,648
   And I think it was because   
        he had bad asthma       

1507
01:30:22,751 --> 01:30:26,753
          <i> and he hated</i>         
        <i> the medication.</i>        

1508
01:30:26,855 --> 01:30:30,089
       <i> It made him speedy</i>      

1509
01:30:30,191 --> 01:30:32,792
      <i> and sort of jagged.</i>      

1510
01:30:32,894 --> 01:30:36,228
       He eventually moved      
          to Washington         

1511
01:30:36,330 --> 01:30:39,098
       and that's sort of       
       when we kind of had      

1512
01:30:39,200 --> 01:30:42,435
            a natural           
       breaking off point.      

1513
01:30:43,805 --> 01:30:45,905
          <i> It was just</i>          
      <i> kind of a beautiful,</i>     

1514
01:30:46,007 --> 01:30:49,041
     <i> bittersweet good-bye.</i>     

1515
01:30:49,143 --> 01:30:51,176
          I don't know.         
     I don't know why I will    
         always remember        

1516
01:30:51,279 --> 01:30:55,448
      that he was wearing--     
     it was a slightly silly    
  red flannel shirt and jeans.  

1517
01:30:57,552 --> 01:31:01,421
        <i> That was my last</i>       
        <i> glimpse of him.</i>        

1518
01:31:06,093 --> 01:31:08,394
          <i> ( clapping )</i>         

1519
01:31:09,631 --> 01:31:10,930
             Cooper:            
       <i> I was on crew team</i>      

1520
01:31:11,032 --> 01:31:12,532
     <i> and I had a crew race</i>     
          <i> in New York</i>          

1521
01:31:12,634 --> 01:31:14,434
     <i> and he came to see it.</i>    

1522
01:31:14,536 --> 01:31:17,102
         <i> And afterward</i>         
       <i> we went back home</i>       

1523
01:31:17,204 --> 01:31:19,305
  <i> and for the first time ever</i>  

1524
01:31:19,407 --> 01:31:21,541
       <i> he seemed to be in</i>      
 <i> some sort of disturbed state.</i> 

1525
01:31:21,643 --> 01:31:24,343
      <i> And he was sleeping</i>      
       <i> at my mom's house.</i>      

1526
01:31:24,446 --> 01:31:26,879
         He clearly had         
         some sort of--         

1527
01:31:26,981 --> 01:31:28,915
      was having some sort      
         of emotional...        

1528
01:31:30,518 --> 01:31:32,552
        I don't know even       
   how to describe it, really.  

1529
01:31:32,654 --> 01:31:34,320
           It was like          
         he was scared.         

1530
01:31:34,422 --> 01:31:36,456
             <i> My mom</i>            
       <i> was very concerned</i>      

1531
01:31:36,558 --> 01:31:39,258
     <i> and he started seeing</i>     
 <i> a therapist right after that.</i> 

1532
01:31:39,360 --> 01:31:41,393
   <i> I happened to run into him</i>  
         <i> on the street</i>         

1533
01:31:41,496 --> 01:31:43,996
         <i> in early July,</i>        
 <i> I think it was July 4 weekend.</i>

1534
01:31:44,098 --> 01:31:46,866
         He said to me,         
    "The last time I saw you,   
     I was like an animal."     

1535
01:31:46,968 --> 01:31:50,402
    And I didn't even really    
        know what to say.       

1536
01:31:52,674 --> 01:31:55,575
    And A, I was so surprised   
  to sort of just run into him  

1537
01:31:55,677 --> 01:31:58,243
            and I was           
        so kind of happy        

1538
01:31:58,346 --> 01:32:01,814
    that he could make light    
   about the way he had been.   

1539
01:32:01,916 --> 01:32:04,584
   To me it just seemed like,   
     okay, well, he's making    
         light about it,        

1540
01:32:04,686 --> 01:32:06,586
      so it can't have been     
          that serious.         

1541
01:32:06,688 --> 01:32:09,822
    So I didn't even really--   
           I think I--          

1542
01:32:09,924 --> 01:32:11,757
        I don't even know       
    what I said in response.    

1543
01:32:11,860 --> 01:32:13,659
    And we ended up stopping    
          and having--          

1544
01:32:13,761 --> 01:32:16,295
        we went for lunch       
            together.           

1545
01:32:16,397 --> 01:32:19,732
   And that was the last time   
           I saw him.           

1546
01:32:19,834 --> 01:32:22,267
          ( cheering )          

1547
01:32:22,370 --> 01:32:24,169
              Marx:             
        <i> It was the night</i>       
          <i> that Dukakis</i>         

1548
01:32:24,271 --> 01:32:29,509
   gave his acceptance speech   
  at the Democratic nomination. 

1549
01:32:29,611 --> 01:32:31,577
    And I was with my sister    

1550
01:32:31,679 --> 01:32:33,746
       and he was talking       
           about jobs.          

1551
01:32:33,848 --> 01:32:36,482
            Dukakis:            
       <i> Jobs you can raise</i>      
          <i> a family on.</i>         

1552
01:32:36,584 --> 01:32:38,618
       <i> Jobs you can build</i>      
          <i> a future on.</i>         

1553
01:32:38,720 --> 01:32:40,285
     <i> Jobs you can count on.</i>    

1554
01:32:40,388 --> 01:32:43,422
              Marx:             
        <i> My sister said,</i>        
        <i> "Jobs you hate."</i>       

1555
01:32:43,525 --> 01:32:45,491
           <i> ( laughs )</i>          
      <i> So I sort of giggled</i>     

1556
01:32:45,593 --> 01:32:48,995
       and I called Carter      
      to just tell him this     
   funny line of my sister's.   

1557
01:32:49,096 --> 01:32:50,997
             <i> And...</i>            

1558
01:32:53,334 --> 01:32:55,234
     <i> he was very emotional.</i>    

1559
01:32:55,336 --> 01:32:57,202
          <i> And I said,</i>          
         <i> "What is it?"</i>         

1560
01:32:59,007 --> 01:33:02,141
       <i> He started crying.</i>      

1561
01:33:02,243 --> 01:33:05,344
     He asked me if I would     
      come over that night.     

1562
01:33:05,446 --> 01:33:08,247
       And it's just awful      
     to think about it now,     

1563
01:33:08,349 --> 01:33:10,850
       but I had a pimple.      

1564
01:33:10,952 --> 01:33:13,819
       Like quite a large,      
        substantial one.        

1565
01:33:13,922 --> 01:33:16,088
           And I just           
    thought, "You know what?    
       I don't want to go.      

1566
01:33:16,190 --> 01:33:18,925
      I love him and, like,     
   I'm still in love with him   

1567
01:33:19,027 --> 01:33:21,561
     and I don't want to go     
      over there with this,     
       you know, pimple."       

1568
01:33:21,663 --> 01:33:23,996
     And I said, "Why don't     
   we get together tomorrow?"   

1569
01:33:27,735 --> 01:33:32,071
           Vanderbilt:          
   <i> It was one of the hottest</i>   
       <i> days in the summer</i>      

1570
01:33:32,173 --> 01:33:34,740
       <i> and he didn't want</i>      
    <i> the air conditioning on,</i>   

1571
01:33:34,842 --> 01:33:37,509
      <i> so it was very hot.</i>      

1572
01:33:37,612 --> 01:33:41,013
   And I think he fell asleep   
     and I think he woke up     

1573
01:33:41,115 --> 01:33:45,317
       and I think he was       
      totally disoriented.      

1574
01:33:45,419 --> 01:33:47,286
          'Cause I know         
     when he came in to me,     

1575
01:33:47,388 --> 01:33:50,255
      I mean, he was like,      
        "What's going on?       
        What's going on?"       

1576
01:33:50,357 --> 01:33:52,224
          He was dazed.         

1577
01:33:52,326 --> 01:33:54,994
        And then he ran.        

1578
01:33:55,096 --> 01:33:58,097
      And I ran after him.      
      I said, "What is it?      
      What it is, Carter?"      

1579
01:33:58,199 --> 01:34:01,233
  <i> And he ran through the hall</i>  
     <i> and ran up the stairs</i>     

1580
01:34:01,335 --> 01:34:03,102
        <i> and ran through</i>        
           <i> your room.</i>          

1581
01:34:03,204 --> 01:34:06,405
      And the terrace door      
            was open.           

1582
01:34:06,507 --> 01:34:09,075
      <i> And I ran after him.</i>     

1583
01:34:09,176 --> 01:34:13,579
    And when I got up there,    

1584
01:34:13,681 --> 01:34:16,682
         he was sitting         
          on the ledge          

1585
01:34:16,784 --> 01:34:20,720
        with one knee up        
       and one knee down.       

1586
01:34:20,822 --> 01:34:24,757
      <i> He was looking down,</i>     
           <i> you know?</i>           

1587
01:34:24,859 --> 01:34:27,392
          I was really          
     very close behind him.     

1588
01:34:27,495 --> 01:34:29,095
           I mean, I--          

1589
01:34:29,196 --> 01:34:31,764
      and I said, "Carter,      
      what are you doing?"      

1590
01:34:31,866 --> 01:34:34,900
     And he put his hand up     
     because I started to go    
          towards him.          

1591
01:34:35,003 --> 01:34:37,036
     And he put his hand up     
           to stop me.          

1592
01:34:37,138 --> 01:34:40,806
         And I thought,         

1593
01:34:40,908 --> 01:34:43,575
        you know, if I--        
       what I wanted to do      

1594
01:34:43,678 --> 01:34:46,612
  was take him and grab one arm 
        and grab him off,       

1595
01:34:46,714 --> 01:34:50,149
    <i> but I thought that might</i>   
    <i> send him over, you know?</i>   

1596
01:34:50,251 --> 01:34:54,086
   And then I started getting   
        down on my knees.       

1597
01:34:54,188 --> 01:34:57,389
        I said, "I beg--"       
   and he said, "Don't, don't.  
    Get up, get up, get up."    

1598
01:34:57,491 --> 01:34:59,625
          So I got up.          

1599
01:34:59,727 --> 01:35:01,127
            ( sighs )           

1600
01:35:01,228 --> 01:35:05,464
      <i> And then he started</i>      
     <i> looking up at the sky</i>     

1601
01:35:05,566 --> 01:35:09,601
     <i> and there were planes</i>     
          <i> coming over.</i>         

1602
01:35:09,704 --> 01:35:14,406
        <i> He looked at one</i>       
    <i> and it was kind of like</i>    
        <i> it was a signal.</i>       

1603
01:35:14,508 --> 01:35:18,010
       And then he jumped       
  and he hung onto the ledge... 

1604
01:35:21,182 --> 01:35:23,683
          hanging down.         

1605
01:35:23,785 --> 01:35:26,218
           And I said,          
      "Carter, come back."      

1606
01:35:27,789 --> 01:35:29,889
    And then he just let go.    

1607
01:35:29,991 --> 01:35:32,624
       And it all happened      
           like that.           

1608
01:35:35,229 --> 01:35:37,462
            ( sighs )           

1609
01:35:53,214 --> 01:35:56,415
             Cooper:            
     <i> It's crazy to me that</i>     
 <i> I've lived longer without him</i> 

1610
01:35:56,517 --> 01:35:58,350
     <i> than I lived with him.</i>    

1611
01:35:58,452 --> 01:36:01,653
   There's moments that still   
 hits me like a punch in the gut

1612
01:36:01,756 --> 01:36:04,023
       and I literally get      
   sort of vertigo or nausea.   

1613
01:36:04,125 --> 01:36:07,927
     I still cannot believe     
        the way he died.        

1614
01:36:08,029 --> 01:36:10,696
      I cannot believe it.      

1615
01:36:19,573 --> 01:36:22,307
     -<i> How did you survive?</i>     
     - I really just cried.     

1616
01:36:22,409 --> 01:36:26,879
        I cried and cried       
      and cried and cried.      

1617
01:36:26,981 --> 01:36:29,915
       And cried and cried      
           and cried.           

1618
01:36:34,321 --> 01:36:37,589
             Cooper:            
       <i> You know, I think</i>       
        <i> my mom early on</i>        

1619
01:36:37,691 --> 01:36:42,194
         and maybe still        
    to this day doesn't refer   
   to it so much as a suicide,  

1620
01:36:42,296 --> 01:36:43,796
         'cause I think         
    she has the impression--    

1621
01:36:43,898 --> 01:36:45,898
  I think a lot of people do--  
      that the term suicide     

1622
01:36:46,000 --> 01:36:47,466
     implies that there was     
      some sort of intent.      

1623
01:36:47,568 --> 01:36:49,168
     That there's some sort     
         of, you know--         

1624
01:36:49,270 --> 01:36:52,071
      this was a conscious,     
         intentious act.        

1625
01:36:52,173 --> 01:36:55,241
    I don't know that he knew   
       what he was doing.       

1626
01:36:55,342 --> 01:36:59,478
      I mean, I don't know      
     that he was wanting to     
      finally end his life.     

1627
01:36:59,580 --> 01:37:02,581
            I believe           
      he had some impulse.      

1628
01:37:02,683 --> 01:37:04,917
         <i> Perhaps he had</i>        
         <i> had it before</i>         

1629
01:37:05,019 --> 01:37:08,720
   <i> or some overwhelming fear</i>   
      <i> or whatever it was.</i>      

1630
01:37:10,658 --> 01:37:14,260
           It was just          
       an unbearable loss.      

1631
01:37:14,361 --> 01:37:16,762
          And a crazy,          
         senseless one.         

1632
01:37:19,233 --> 01:37:21,133
      <i> It is inconceivable</i>      

1633
01:37:21,235 --> 01:37:25,604
       <i> that he would have</i>      
      <i> jumped off the roof</i>      
    <i> in front of his mother.</i>    

1634
01:37:27,708 --> 01:37:30,742
           Vanderbilt:          
   <i> I thought the worst thing</i>   
  <i> that had ever happened to me</i> 

1635
01:37:30,845 --> 01:37:34,113
         was, you know,         
        when I was nine,        

1636
01:37:34,215 --> 01:37:36,615
         but that wasn't        
           the worst.           

1637
01:37:36,717 --> 01:37:39,185
            The worst           
       is to lose a child.      

1638
01:38:07,481 --> 01:38:09,548
            I thought           
     of going over with him.    

1639
01:38:11,219 --> 01:38:13,185
       Almost did, really.      

1640
01:38:13,287 --> 01:38:15,988
    <i> Except I thought of you.</i>   

1641
01:38:25,799 --> 01:38:28,300
            You know,           
        I feel so that--        

1642
01:38:31,205 --> 01:38:33,705
        I mean, I failed        
       so much in my life       

1643
01:38:33,807 --> 01:38:35,875
     and I just, you know...    

1644
01:39:14,748 --> 01:39:17,049
     I haven't been             
     out here since...          

1645
01:39:19,020 --> 01:39:21,787
       -<i> The funeral.</i>           
       - I think since          
       the funeral, yeah.       

1646
01:39:32,499 --> 01:39:34,699
       <i> ( snow crunching )</i>      

1647
01:39:41,542 --> 01:39:43,809
       ( sighs )                

1648
01:39:48,849 --> 01:39:51,083
          <i> ( scraping )</i>         

1649
01:39:58,960 --> 01:40:01,260
           Vanderbilt:          
         <i> That does it.</i>         

1650
01:40:12,539 --> 01:40:14,606
                 ( exhales )    

1651
01:40:16,510 --> 01:40:18,110
       <i> ( bird chirping )</i>       

1652
01:40:29,790 --> 01:40:33,192
You know, and I think           
if I would've only picked up    
the fire--                      

1653
01:40:33,294 --> 01:40:36,328
the thing in the fireplace      
 and hit him over the head      

1654
01:40:36,430 --> 01:40:39,131
 when he started running        
up the stairs, you know?        

1655
01:40:41,202 --> 01:40:43,469
But it happened                 
so quickly.                     

1656
01:40:52,646 --> 01:40:54,179
( sniffles )                    

1657
01:40:54,281 --> 01:40:55,780
         It's nice to see them  
         side by side.          

1658
01:40:55,883 --> 01:40:57,616
   Yes, it is.                  

1659
01:41:06,793 --> 01:41:09,995
You know, I think               
it's sort of one thing          
I was able to give him.         

1660
01:41:12,799 --> 01:41:14,333
         - Do you know?         
         - Mm-hmm.              

1661
01:41:14,435 --> 01:41:16,868
      - I mean,                 
      if it had to happen.      
      - Mm-hmm.                 

1662
01:41:18,872 --> 01:41:21,840
It would be inconceivable       
to him, you know?               

1663
01:41:24,245 --> 01:41:27,212
I mean, it was                  
to all of us, really,           
you know?                       

1664
01:41:50,337 --> 01:41:52,003
              ( sniffles )      

1665
01:42:05,953 --> 01:42:08,720
  Maybe we'll come here         
  in the spring sometime.       

1666
01:42:12,693 --> 01:42:15,127
  It's really pretty then.      

1667
01:42:17,264 --> 01:42:19,565
       <i> ( opera playing )</i>       

1668
01:42:39,353 --> 01:42:41,220
             Cooper:            
      <i> You know, the thing</i>      
      <i> I ultimately came to</i>     

1669
01:42:41,322 --> 01:42:43,489
        is that sometimes       
      there isn't any why.      

1670
01:42:43,591 --> 01:42:47,159
   Or sometimes there is no--   
 you can't get an answer exactly
   of why something happened.   

1671
01:42:47,261 --> 01:42:49,394
   There's no way to actually   
       get a final answer.      

1672
01:42:49,497 --> 01:42:52,097
       <i> And you just have</i>       
           <i> to be able</i>          

1673
01:42:52,199 --> 01:42:54,733
        <i> to kind of live</i>        
    <i> in a world without why.</i>    

1674
01:43:57,931 --> 01:43:59,665
             Woman:             
    <i> Good evening, everyone.</i>    

1675
01:43:59,766 --> 01:44:02,267
    <i> I'd like to welcome you</i>    
    <i> to the Carter V. Cooper</i>    

1676
01:44:02,369 --> 01:44:04,703
          <i> Annual Award</i>         
          <i> for Short Fiction.</i>   

1677
01:44:04,805 --> 01:44:08,574
           It was an award      
           that was established 
           by Gloria Vanderbilt 

1678
01:44:08,676 --> 01:44:12,844
          <i> in memory of her son</i> 
          <i> Carter Cooper.</i>       

1679
01:44:18,185 --> 01:44:21,286
           Vanderbilt:          
       <i> "Say not of beauty</i>      
          <i> she is good,</i>         

1680
01:44:21,388 --> 01:44:23,322
    <i> Or aught but beautiful,</i>    

1681
01:44:23,424 --> 01:44:27,459
    <i> Or sleek to doves' wings</i>   
          <i> of the wood</i>          

1682
01:44:27,561 --> 01:44:30,429
         <i> Her wild wings</i>        
           <i> of a gull.</i>          

1683
01:44:30,531 --> 01:44:32,397
      <i> Call her not wicked;</i>     

1684
01:44:32,499 --> 01:44:36,935
That word's touch               
consumes her like a curse;      

1685
01:44:37,037 --> 01:44:39,804
But love her not                
too much, too much,             

1686
01:44:39,906 --> 01:44:41,673
For that is even worse.         

1687
01:44:41,775 --> 01:44:45,009
<i>O, she is neither</i>               
<i>good nor bad,</i>                   

1688
01:44:45,112 --> 01:44:47,312
But innocent and wild,          

1689
01:44:47,414 --> 01:44:50,282
Enshrine her                    
and she dies,                   

1690
01:44:50,384 --> 01:44:54,219
Who had the hard heart          
of a child."                    

1691
01:44:57,157 --> 01:44:59,424
               What does        
               that mean to you?

1692
01:44:59,526 --> 01:45:01,360
   What does it                 
   mean to you?                 

1693
01:45:01,462 --> 01:45:03,962
                  What does it  
                  mean to you?  

1694
01:45:04,064 --> 01:45:05,897
It means to me                  
that I had                      

1695
01:45:05,999 --> 01:45:09,368
